# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battery-chemistry-embedded
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A **battery charger**, **recharger**, or simply **charger**, is a device that stores energy in an electric battery by running current through it.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The charging protocol—how much voltage and current, for how long and what to do when charging is complete—depends on the size and type of the battery being charged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some battery types have high tolerance for overcharging after the battery has been fully charged and can be recharged by connection to a constant voltage source or a constant current source, depending on battery type.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Simple chargers of this type must be manually disconnected at the end of the charge cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Other battery types use a timer to cut off when charging should be complete.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Other battery types cannot withstand over-charging, becoming damaged (reduced capacity, reduced lifetime), over heating or even exploding.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The charger may have temperature or voltage sensing circuits and a microprocessor controller to safely adjust the charging current and voltage, determine the state of charge, and cut off at the end of charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Chargers may elevate the output voltage proportionally with current to compensate for impedance in the wires.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A trickle charger provides a relatively small amount of current, only enough to counteract self-discharge of a battery that is idle for a long time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some battery types cannot tolerate trickle charging; attempts to do so may result in damage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Lithium-ion batteries cannot handle indefinite trickle charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Slow battery chargers may take several hours to complete a charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] High-rate chargers may restore most capacity much faster, but high-rate chargers can be more than some battery types can tolerate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Such batteries require active monitoring of the battery to protect it from any abusive use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Electric vehicles ideally need high-rate chargers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] For public access, installation of such chargers and the distribution support for them is an issue in the proposed adoption of electric cars.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Charge and discharge rates are often given as *C* or *C-rate*, which is a measure of the rate at which a battery is charged or discharged relative to its capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The C-rate is defined as the charge or discharge current divided by the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] While rarely stated explicitly, the unit of the C-rate is h−1, equivalent to stating the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge in unit hour times current in the same unit as the charge or discharge current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The C-rate is never negative, so whether it describes a charging or discharging process depends on the context.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] For example, for a battery with a capacity of 500 mAh, a discharge rate of 5000 mA (i.e., 5 A) corresponds to a C-rate of 10C, meaning that such a current can discharge 10 such batteries in one hour.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Likewise, for the same battery a charge current of 250 mA corresponds to a C-rate of C/2, meaning that this current will increase the state of charge of this battery by 50% in one hour.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Running current through batteries generates internal heat, roughly proportional to the current involved (a battery's current state of charge, condition / history, etc. are also factors).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] If the charging process is endothermic (which is the case for Ni–Cd batteries, whereas charging nickel–metal hydride batteries is exothermic) the charging process initially cools the battery, but as it reaches full charge, the cooling effect stops and the cell heats up.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Detecting a temperature rise of 10 °C (18 °F) is one way of determining when to stop charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Battery cells which have been built to allow higher C-rates than usual must make provision for increased heating.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] But high C-ratings are attractive to end users because such batteries can be charged more quickly, and produce higher current output in use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] High C-rates typically require the charger to carefully monitor battery parameters such as terminal voltage and temperature to prevent overcharging and so damage to the cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Such high-charging rates are possible only with some battery types.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Others will be damaged or possibly overheat or catch fire.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] For example, an automobile SLI (starting, lighting, ignition) lead–acid battery carries several risks of explosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A simple charger works by supplying a constant DC or pulsed DC power source to a battery being charged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A simple charger typically does not alter its output based on charging time or the charge on the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] This simplicity means that a simple charger is inexpensive, but there are tradeoffs.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Typically, a carefully designed simple charger takes longer to charge a battery because it is set to use a lower (i.e., safer) charging rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Even so, many batteries left on a simple charger for too long will be weakened or destroyed due to over-charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] These chargers also vary in that they can supply either a constant voltage or a constant current, to the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Simple AC-powered battery chargers usually have much higher ripple current and ripple voltage than other kinds of battery chargers because they are inexpensively designed and built.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Generally, when the ripple current is within a battery's manufacturer recommended level, the ripple voltage will also be well within the recommended level.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The maximum ripple current for a typical 12 V 100 Ah VRLA battery is 5 amperes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] As long as the ripple current is not excessive (more than 3 to 4 times the level recommended by the battery manufacturer), the expected life of a ripple-charged VRLA battery will be within 3% of the life of a constant DC-charged battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Fast chargers make use of control circuitry to rapidly charge the batteries without damaging any of the cells in the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The control circuitry can be built into the battery (generally for each cell) or in the external charging unit, or split between both.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Most such chargers have a cooling fan to help keep the temperature of the cells at safe levels.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Most fast chargers are also capable of acting as standard overnight chargers if used with standard Ni–MH cells that do not have the special control circuitry.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] To accelerate the charging time and provide continuous charging, an intelligent charger attempts to detect the state of charge and condition of the battery and applies a three-stage charging scheme.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The following description assumes a sealed lead–acid traction battery at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The first stage is referred to as "bulk absorption"; the charging current is held high and constant and is limited by the capacity of the charger.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] When the voltage on the battery reaches its outgassing voltage (2.22 volts per cell) the charger switches to the second stage, and the voltage is held constant (2.40 volts per cell).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The delivered current declines at the maintained voltage, and when the current reaches less than 0.005C the charger enters its third stage and the charger output is held constant at 2.25 volts per cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] In the third stage, the charging current is very small, 0.005C, and at this voltage the battery can be maintained at full charge and compensate for self-discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers use electromagnetic induction to charge batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A charging station sends electromagnetic energy through inductive coupling to an electrical device, which stores the energy in the batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] This is achieved without the need for metal contacts between the charger and the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers are commonly used in electric toothbrushes and other devices used in bathrooms.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Because there are no open electrical contacts, there is no risk of electrocution.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Nowadays it is being used to charge wireless phones.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A smart charger can respond to the condition of a battery and modify its charging parameters accordingly, whereas "dumb" chargers apply a steady voltage, possibly through a fixed resistance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] It should not be confused with a smart battery that contains a computer chip and communicates digitally with a smart charger about battery condition.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A smart battery requires a smart charger.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some smart chargers can also charge "dumb" batteries, which lack any internal electronics.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The output current of a smart charger depends upon the battery's state.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] An intelligent charger may monitor the battery's voltage, temperature or charge time to determine the optimum charge current or terminate charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] For Ni–Cd and Ni–MH batteries, the voltage of the battery increases slowly during the charging process, until the battery is fully charged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] After that, the voltage *decreases* because of increasing temperature, which indicates to an intelligent charger that the battery is fully charged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Such chargers are often labeled as a ΔV, "delta-V", or sometimes "delta peak" charger, indicating that they monitor voltage change.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] This can cause even an intelligent charger not to sense that the batteries are already fully charged, and continue charging, the result of which may be overcharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Many intelligent chargers employ a variety of cut-off systems to prevent overcharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A typical smart charger fast-charges a battery up to about 85% of its maximum capacity in less than an hour, then switches to trickle charging, which takes several hours to top off the battery to its full capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Several companies have begun making devices that charge batteries using energy from human motion, such as walking.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] An example, made by Tremont Electric, consists of a magnet held between two springs that can charge a battery as the device is moved up and down.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Such products have not yet achieved significant commercial success.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A pedal-powered charger for mobile phones fitted into desks has been created for installation in public spaces, such as airports, railway stations and universities.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] They have been installed in a number of countries on several continents.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some chargers use *pulse technology*, in which a series of electrical pulses is fed to the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The DC pulses have a strictly controlled rise time, pulse width, pulse repetition rate (frequency) and amplitude.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] This technology works with any size and type of battery, including automotive and valve-regulated ones.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] With pulse charging, high instantaneous voltages are applied without overheating the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] In a lead–acid battery, this breaks down lead-sulfate crystals, thus greatly extending the battery service life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Several kinds of pulse chargers are patented, while others are open source hardware.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some chargers use pulses to check the current battery state when the charger is first connected, then use constant current charging during fast charge, then use pulse mode to trickle charge it.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some chargers use "negative pulse charging", also called "reflex charging" or "burp charging".
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] These chargers use both positive and brief negative current pulses.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] There is no significant evidence that negative pulse charging is more effective than ordinary pulse charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Solar chargers convert light energy into low-voltage DC current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] They are generally portable, but can also be fixed mounted.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Fixed mount solar chargers are also known as solar panels.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] These are often connected to the electrical grid via control and interface circuits, whereas portable solar chargers are used off-grid (i.e. cars, boats, or RVs).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Although portable solar chargers obtain energy only from the sun, they can charge in low light like at sunset.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Portable solar chargers are often used for trickle charging, though some can completely recharge batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The output of a timer charger is terminated after a predetermined time interval.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Timer chargers were the most common type for high-capacity Ni–Cd cells in the late 1990s to charge low-capacity consumer Ni–Cd cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Often a timer charger and set of batteries could be bought as a bundle and the charger time is set for those batteries specifically.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] If batteries of lower capacity are charged, then they would be overcharged, and if batteries of higher capacity were timer-charged, they would not reach full capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Timer based chargers also had the drawback that charging batteries that were not fully discharged would result in over-charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A trickle charger is typically low-current (usually between 5–1,500 mA).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] They are generally used to charge small capacity batteries (2–30 Ah).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] They are also used to maintain larger capacity batteries (> 30 Ah) in cars and boats.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] In larger applications, the current of the battery charger is only sufficient to provide trickle current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Depending on the technology of the trickle charger, it can be left connected to the battery indefinitely.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some battery types are not suitable for trickle charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] For instance, most Li-ion batteries cannot be safely trickle charged and can cause a fire or explosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Charge DC (battery) from DC source without conversion to AC.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Modern DC-DC chargers often include isolator and DC-DC converter.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some may also have BMS (including balance), be bidirectional (jump start primary car battery from secondary battery) and wireless control (Bluetooth, WiFi, NFC, 5G).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The most sophisticated chargers are used in critical applications (e.g. military or aviation batteries).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] These heavy-duty automatic "intelligent charging" systems can be programmed with complex charging cycles specified by the battery manufacturer.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The best are universal (i.e. can charge all battery types), and include automatic capacity testing and analyzing functions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Since the Universal Serial Bus specification provides five-volt power, it is possible to use a USB cable to connect a device to a power supply.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Products based on this approach include chargers for cellular phones, portable digital audio players, and tablet computers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] They may be fully compliant USB peripheral devices or uncontrolled, simple chargers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Another type of USB charger called "USB (rechargeable) battery" is fitted into the case of standard batteries (1.5 V AA, C, D, and 9 V block) together with a Li-ion rechargeable battery, voltage converter, and USB connector.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Since a battery charger is intended to be connected to a battery, it may not have voltage regulation or filtering of the DC voltage output; it is cheaper to make them that way.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Battery chargers equipped with both voltage regulation and filtering are sometimes termed battery eliminators.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Chargers for car batteries come in varying ratings.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Chargers that are rated up to two amperes may be used to maintain charge on parked vehicle batteries or for small batteries on garden tractors or similar equipment.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A motorist may keep a charger rated a few amperes to ten or fifteen amperes for maintenance of automobile batteries or to recharge a vehicle battery that has accidentally discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Service stations and commercial garages will have a large charger to fully charge a battery in an hour or two; often these chargers can briefly source the hundreds of amperes required to crank an internal combustion engine starter.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Electric vehicle battery chargers (ECS) come in a variety of brands and characteristics.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] These chargers vary from 1 kW to 22 kW maximum charge rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some use algorithm charge curves, others use constant voltage, constant current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some are programmable by the end user through a CAN port, some have dials for maximum voltage and amperage, some are preset to specified battery pack voltage, ampere-hour and chemistry.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A 10-ampere-hour battery could take 15 hours to reach a fully charged state from a fully discharged condition with a 1-ampere charger as it would require roughly 1.5 times the battery's capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Public EV charging stations often provide 6 kW (host power of 208 to 240 V AC off a 40-ampere circuit).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] 6 kW will recharge an EV roughly six times faster than 1 kW overnight charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Rapid charging results in even faster recharge times and is limited only by available AC power, battery type, and the type of charging system.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Power-factor correction (PFC) chargers can more closely approach the maximum current the plug can deliver, shortening charging time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Project Better Place was deploying a network of charging stations and subsidizing vehicle battery costs through leases and credits until filing for bankruptcy in May 2013.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Most mobile phone chargers are not really chargers, only power adapters that provide a power source for the charging circuitry which is almost always contained within the mobile phone.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some higher-end models feature multiple ports which are equipped with a display which indicates output current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Some support communication protocols for charging parameters such as Qualcomm Quick Charge or MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Chargers for 12 V automobile auxiliary power outlets may support input voltages of up to 24 or 32 V DC to ensure compatibility, and are sometimes equipped with a display to monitor current or the voltage of the vehicle's electrical system.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] China, the European Union, and other countries are making a national standard on mobile phone chargers using the USB standard.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] In June 2009, 10 of the world's largest mobile phone manufacturers signed a Memorandum of Understanding to develop specifications for and support a microUSB-equipped common external power supply (EPS) for all data-enabled mobile phones sold in the EU.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] On October 22, 2009, the International Telecommunication Union announced that microUSB would be the standard for a universal charger for mobile handsets.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] In October 2022 the EU's Common Charger Directive was approved with the new rules applying to mobile phones and a number of other devices, which came into force in December 2024.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Telecommunications, electric power, and computer uninterruptible power supply facilities may have very large standby battery banks (installed in battery rooms) to maintain critical loads for several hours during interruptions of primary grid power.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Such chargers are permanently installed and equipped with temperature compensation, supervisory alarms for various system faults, and often redundant independent power supplies and redundant rectifier systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Chargers for stationary battery plants may have adequate voltage regulation and filtration and sufficient current capacity to allow the battery to be disconnected for maintenance, while the charger supplies the direct current (DC) system load.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The capacity of the charger is specified to maintain the system load and recharge a completely discharged battery within, say, 8 hours or other intervals.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] A properly designed charger can allow batteries to reach their full cycle life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Excess charging current, lengthy overcharging, or cell reversal in a multiple cell pack cause damage to cells and limit the life expectancy of a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Most modern cell phones, laptop and tablet computers, and most electric vehicles use lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] These batteries last longest if the battery is frequently charged; fully discharging the cells will degrade their capacity relatively quickly, but most such batteries are used in equipment which can sense the approach of full discharge and discontinue equipment use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] When stored after charging, lithium battery cells degrade more while fully charged than if they are only 40–50% charged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] As with all battery types, degradation also occurs faster at higher temperatures.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Degradation in lithium-ion batteries is caused by an increased internal battery resistance often due to the cell oxidation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] This decreases the efficiency of the battery, resulting in less net current available to be drawn from the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] However, if Li-ion cells are discharged below a certain voltage a chemical reaction occurs that make them dangerous if recharged, which is why many such batteries in consumer goods now have an "electronic fuse" that permanently disables them if the voltage falls below a set level.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] The electronic fuse circuitry draws a small amount of current from the battery, which means that if a laptop battery is left for a long time without charging it, and with a very low initial state of charge, the battery may be permanently destroyed.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Motor vehicles, such as boats, RVs, ATVs, motorcycles, cars, trucks, etc. have used lead–acid batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] These batteries employ a sulfuric acid electrolyte and can generally be charged and discharged without exhibiting memory effect, though sulfation (a chemical reaction in the battery which deposits a layer of sulfates on the lead) will occur over time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Typically sulfated batteries are simply replaced with new batteries, and the old ones recycled.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Lead–acid batteries will experience substantially longer life when a maintenance charger is used to "float charge" the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] This prevents the battery from ever being below 100% charge, preventing sulfate from forming.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Proper temperature compensated float voltage should be used to achieve the best results.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Battery charging technology is developing to support the increasing demands of electric vehicles (EVs), consumer electronics, and sustainable energy systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Modern chargers may feature Internet of things (IoT) connectivity for real-time monitoring, adaptive charging protocols, remote management, predictive maintenance, and may enhance safety and efficiency.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Artificial intelligence (AI) is being integrated into battery management systems to optimize charging rates, predict battery health, extend usable life, and maximize energy efficiency.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] As a result of electric mobility and smart device proliferation, the global battery charger market is projected (as of 2025) to see significant growth over the following decade.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-charger] Smart chargers integrating IoT, AI, and adaptive features are expected to outpace traditional models globally.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] An **electric battery** is a source of electric power consisting of one or more electrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] When a battery is supplying power, its positive terminal is the cathode and its negative terminal is the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The terminal marked negative is the source of electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] When a battery is connected to an external electric load, those negatively charged electrons flow through the circuit and reach the positive terminal, thus causing a redox reaction by attracting positively charged ions, or cations.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Thus, higher energy reactants are converted to lower energy products, and the free-energy difference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Historically the term "battery" specifically referred to a device composed of multiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a single cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Primary (single-use or "disposable") batteries are used once and discarded, as the electrode materials are irreversibly changed during discharge; a common example is the alkaline battery used for flashlights and a multitude of portable electronic devices.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Secondary (rechargeable) batteries can be discharged and recharged multiple times using an applied electric current; the original composition of the electrodes can be restored by reverse current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Examples include the lead–acid automotive battery used in internal combustion engine vehicles, and lithium-ion batteries used for portable electronics and electric cars.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries come in many shapes and sizes, from miniature cells used to power hearing aids and wristwatches to, at the largest extreme, huge battery banks the size of rooms that provide standby or emergency power for telephone exchanges and computer data centers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries have much lower specific energy (energy per unit mass) than common fuels such as gasoline.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In automobiles, this is somewhat offset by the higher efficiency of electric motors in converting electrical energy to mechanical work, compared to combustion engines.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Benjamin Franklin first used the term "battery" in 1749 when he was doing experiments with electricity using a set of linked Leyden jar capacitors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Franklin grouped a number of the jars into what he described as a "battery", using the military term for weapons functioning together.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] By multiplying the number of holding vessels, a stronger charge could be stored, and more power would be available on discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Italian physicist Alessandro Volta built and described the first electrochemical battery, the voltaic pile, in 1800.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] This was a stack of copper and zinc plates, separated by brine-soaked paper disks, that could produce a steady current for a considerable length of time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Volta did not understand that the voltage was due to chemical reactions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] He thought that his cells were an inexhaustible source of energy, and that the associated corrosion effects at the electrodes were a mere nuisance, rather than an unavoidable consequence of their operation, as Michael Faraday showed in 1834.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Although early batteries were of great value for experimental purposes, in practice their voltages fluctuated and they could not provide a large current for a sustained period.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The Daniell cell, invented in 1836 by British chemist John Frederic Daniell, was the first practical source of electricity, becoming an industry standard and seeing widespread adoption as a power source for electrical telegraph networks.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] It consisted of a copper pot filled with a copper sulfate solution, in which was immersed an unglazed earthenware container filled with sulfuric acid and a zinc electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] These wet cells used liquid electrolytes, which were prone to leakage and spillage if not handled correctly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Many used glass jars to hold their components, which made them fragile and potentially dangerous.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] These characteristics made wet cells unsuitable for portable appliances.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Near the end of the nineteenth century, the invention of dry cell batteries, which replaced the liquid electrolyte with a paste, made portable electrical devices practical.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries in vacuum tube devices historically used a wet cell for the "A" battery (to provide power to the filament) and a dry cell for the "B" battery (to provide the plate voltage).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Between 2010 and 2018, battery demand grew by 30% annually, reaching a total of 180 GWh in 2018.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Conservatively, the growth rate is expected to be maintained at an estimated 25%, culminating in demand reaching 2600 GWh in 2030.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In addition, cost reductions are expected to further increase the demand to as much as 3562 GWh.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Important reasons for this high rate of growth of the electric battery industry include the electrification of transport, and large-scale deployment in electricity grids, supported by decarbonization initiatives.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Distributed electric batteries, such as those used in battery electric vehicles (vehicle-to-grid) and in home energy storage with smart metering and that are connected to smart grids for demand response are active participants in smart power supply grids.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Secondary use of partially depleted batteries can add to the overall utility of electric batteries by reducing energy storage costs and emission impact due to longer service life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In this use, vehicle electric batteries that have their battery capacity reduced to less than 80% (usually after 5–8 years of service) are repurposed for use in backup supplies or renewable energy storage systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage envisages the large-scale use of batteries to collect and store energy from the grid or a power plant and then discharge that energy at a later time to provide electricity or other grid services when needed.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage (either turnkey or distributed) are important components of smart power supply grids.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The advent of computational modeling has revolutionized battery materials design, enabling high-throughput screening and atomistic simulations that accelerate the discovery of novel electrolytes and electrodes, moving beyond traditional trial-and-error approaches.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In many cases, the electrical energy released is the difference in the cohesive or bond energies of the metals, oxides, or molecules undergoing the electrochemical reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] For instance, energy can be stored in Zn or Li, which are high-energy metals because they are not stabilized by d-electron bonding, unlike transition metals.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries are designed so that the energetically favorable redox reaction can occur only when electrons move through the external part of the circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A battery consists of some number of voltaic cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Each cell consists of two half-cells connected in series by a conductive electrolyte containing metal *cations*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] One half-cell includes electrolyte and the negative electrode, the electrode to which anions (negatively charged ions) migrate; the other half-cell includes electrolyte and the positive electrode, to which cations (positively charged ions) migrate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Cations are reduced (electrons are added) at the cathode, while metal atoms are oxidized (electrons are removed) at the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Some cells use different electrolytes for each half-cell; then a separator is used to prevent mixing of the electrolytes while allowing ions to flow between half-cells to complete the electrical circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Each half-cell has an electromotive force (*emf*, measured in volts) relative to a standard.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The net emf of the cell is the difference between the emfs of its half-cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Thus, if the electrodes have emfs ${\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}$ , then the net emf is ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}-{\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ ; in other words, the net emf is the difference between the reduction potentials of the half-reactions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The electrical driving force or $\displaystyle {\Delta V_{\text{bat}}}$ across the terminals of a cell is known as the *terminal voltage (difference)* and is measured in volts.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The terminal voltage of a cell that is neither charging nor discharging is called the open-circuit voltage and equals the emf of the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance, the terminal voltage of a cell that is discharging is smaller in magnitude than the open-circuit voltage and the terminal voltage of a cell that is charging exceeds the open-circuit voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] An ideal cell has negligible internal resistance, so it would maintain a constant terminal voltage of ${\mathcal {E}}$ until exhausted, then dropping to zero.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] If such a cell maintained 1.5 volts and produced a charge of one coulomb then on complete discharge it would have performed 1.5 joules of work.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In actual cells, the internal resistance increases under discharge and the open-circuit voltage also decreases under discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] If the voltage and resistance are plotted against time, the resulting graphs typically are a curve; the shape of the curve varies according to the chemistry and internal arrangement employed.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The voltage developed across a cell's terminals depends on the energy release of the chemical reactions of its electrodes and electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Alkaline and zinc–carbon cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.5 volts; likewise NiCd and NiMH cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.2 volts.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The high electrochemical potential changes in the reactions of lithium compounds give lithium cells emfs of 3 volts or more.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Almost any liquid or moist object that has enough ions to be electrically conductive can serve as the electrolyte for a cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] As a novelty or science demonstration, it is possible to insert two electrodes made of different metals into a lemon, potato, etc. and generate small amounts of electricity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A voltaic pile can be made from two coins (such as a nickel and a penny) and a piece of paper towel dipped in salt water.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Such a pile generates a very low voltage but, when many are stacked in series, they can replace normal batteries for a short time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Some types of primary batteries used, for example, for telegraph circuits, were restored to operation by replacing the electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries are not indefinitely rechargeable due to dissipation of the active materials, loss of electrolyte and internal corrosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Primary batteries, or primary cells, can produce current immediately on assembly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] These are most commonly used in portable devices that have low current drain, are used only intermittently, or are used well away from an alternative power source, such as in alarm and communication circuits where other electric power is only intermittently available.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Disposable primary cells cannot be reliably recharged, since the chemical reactions are not easily reversible and active materials may not return to their original forms.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Battery manufacturers recommend against attempting to recharge primary cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In general, these have higher energy densities than rechargeable batteries, but disposable batteries do not fare well under high-drain applications with loads under 75 ohms (75 Ω).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Common types of disposable batteries include zinc–carbon batteries and alkaline batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries, also known as *secondary cells*, or *rechargeable batteries*, must be charged before first use; they are usually assembled with active materials in the discharged state.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Rechargeable batteries are (re)charged by applying electric current, which reverses the chemical reactions that occur during discharge/use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Devices to supply the appropriate current are called chargers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The oldest form of rechargeable battery is the lead–acid battery, which are widely used in automotive and boating applications.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] This technology contains liquid electrolyte in an unsealed container, requiring that the battery be kept upright and the area be well ventilated to ensure safe dispersal of the hydrogen gas it produces during overcharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The lead–acid battery is relatively heavy for the amount of electrical energy it can supply.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Its low manufacturing cost and its high surge current levels make it common where its capacity (over approximately 10 Ah) is more important than weight and handling issues.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A common application is the modern car battery, which can, in general, deliver a peak current of 450 amperes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Many types of electrochemical cells have been produced, with varying chemical processes and designs, including galvanic cells, electrolytic cells, fuel cells, flow cells and voltaic piles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A *wet cell* battery has a liquid electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Other names are *flooded cell*, since the liquid covers all internal parts or *vented cell*, since gases produced during operation can escape to the air.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Wet cells were a precursor to dry cells and are commonly used as a learning tool for electrochemistry.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] They can be built with common laboratory supplies, such as beakers, for demonstrations of how electrochemical cells work.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A particular type of wet cell known as a concentration cell is important in understanding corrosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Wet cells may be primary cells (non-rechargeable) or secondary cells (rechargeable).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Originally, all practical primary batteries, such as the Daniell cell, were built as open-top glass jar wet cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Other primary wet cells are the Leclanche cell, Grove cell, Bunsen cell, Chromic acid cell, Clark cell, and Weston cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The Leclanche cell chemistry was adapted to the first dry cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Wet cells are still used in automobile batteries and in industry for standby power for switchgear, telecommunication or large uninterruptible power supplies, but in many places batteries with gel cells have been used instead.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] These applications commonly use lead–acid or nickel–cadmium cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Molten salt batteries are primary or secondary batteries that use a molten salt as electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] They operate at high temperatures and must be well insulated to retain heat.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A *dry cell* uses a paste electrolyte, with only enough moisture to allow current to flow.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Unlike a wet cell, a dry cell can operate in any orientation without spilling, as it contains no free liquid, making it suitable for portable equipment.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] By comparison, the first wet cells were typically fragile glass containers with lead rods hanging from the open top and needed careful handling to avoid spillage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries did not achieve the safety and portability of the dry cell until the development of the gel battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A common dry cell is the zinc–carbon battery, sometimes called the dry Leclanché cell, with a nominal voltage of 1.5 volts, the same as the alkaline battery (since both use the same zinc–manganese dioxide combination).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A standard dry cell comprises a zinc anode, usually in the form of a cylindrical pot, with a carbon cathode in the form of a central rod.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The electrolyte is ammonium chloride in the form of a paste next to the zinc anode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The remaining space between the electrolyte and carbon cathode is taken up by a second paste consisting of ammonium chloride and manganese dioxide, the latter acting as a depolariser.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In some designs, the ammonium chloride is replaced by zinc chloride.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A reserve battery can be stored unassembled (unactivated and supplying no power) for a long period (perhaps years).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] When the battery is needed, then it is assembled (e.g., by adding electrolyte); once assembled, the battery is charged and ready to work.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] For example, a battery for an electronic artillery fuze might be activated by the impact of firing a gun.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The acceleration breaks a capsule of electrolyte that activates the battery and powers the fuze's circuits.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Reserve batteries are usually designed for a short service life (seconds or minutes) after long storage (years).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A water-activated battery for oceanographic instruments or military applications becomes activated on immersion in water.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The solid-state battery is also said to have "three times the energy density", increasing its useful life in electric vehicles, for example.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] It should also be more ecologically sound since the technology uses less expensive, earth-friendly materials such as sodium extracted from seawater.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Sony has developed a biological battery that generates electricity from sugar in a way that is similar to the processes observed in living organisms.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The battery generates electricity through the use of enzymes that break down carbohydrates.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The sealed valve regulated lead–acid battery (VRLA battery) is popular in the automotive industry as a replacement for the lead–acid wet cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The VRLA battery uses an immobilized sulfuric acid electrolyte, reducing the chance of leakage and extending shelf life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] VRLA batteries immobilize the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Other portable rechargeable batteries include several sealed "dry cell" types, that are useful in applications such as mobile phones and laptop computers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Cells of this type (in order of increasing power density and cost) include nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–zinc (NiZn), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), and lithium-ion (Li-ion) cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Li-ion has by far the highest share of the dry cell rechargeable market.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] NiMH has replaced NiCd in most applications due to its higher capacity, but NiCd remains in use in power tools, two-way radios, and medical equipment.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Low self-discharge (LSD) allows secondary cells to be charged prior to shipping.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Lithium–sulfur batteries were used on the longest and highest solar-powered flight.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries of all types are manufactured in consumer and industrial grades.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Standard-format batteries are inserted into battery holder in the device that uses them.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] When a device does not uses standard-format batteries, they are typically combined into a custom battery pack which holds multiple batteries in addition to features such as a battery management system and battery isolator which ensure that the batteries within are charged and discharged evenly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Primary batteries readily available to consumers range from tiny button cells used for electric watches, to the No.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] 6 cell used for signal circuits or other long duration applications.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Secondary cells are made in very large sizes; very large batteries can power a submarine or stabilize an electrical grid and help level out peak loads.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] As of 2017, the world's largest battery was built in South Australia by Tesla.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A battery in Hebei Province, China, which can store 36 MWh of electricity was built in 2013 at a cost of $500 million.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Another large battery, composed of Ni–Cd cells, was in Fairbanks, Alaska.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] It covered 2,000 square metres (22,000 sq ft)—bigger than a football pitch—and weighed 1,300 tonnes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] It was manufactured by ABB to provide backup power in the event of a blackout.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The battery can provide 40 MW of power for up to seven minutes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Sodium–sulfur batteries have been used to store wind power.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A 4.4 MWh battery system that can deliver 11 MW for 25 minutes stabilizes the output of the Auwahi wind farm in Hawaii.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Many important cell properties, such as voltage, energy density, flammability, available cell constructions, operating temperature range and shelf life, are dictated by battery chemistry.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A battery's characteristics may vary over load cycle, over charge cycle, and over lifetime due to many factors including internal chemistry, current drain, and temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] At low temperatures, a battery cannot deliver as much power.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] As such, in cold climates, some car owners install battery warmers, which are small electric heating pads that keep the car battery warm.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A battery's *capacity* is the amount of electric charge it can deliver at a voltage that does not drop below the specified terminal voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The more electrode material contained in the cell the greater its capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A small cell has less capacity than a larger cell with the same chemistry, although they develop the same open-circuit voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Capacity is usually stated in ampere-hours (A·h) (mAh for small batteries).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The rated capacity of a battery is usually expressed as the product of 20 hours multiplied by the current that a new battery can consistently supply for 20 hours at 20 °C (68 °F), while remaining above a specified terminal voltage per cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 100 A·h can deliver 5 A over a 20-hour period at room temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The fraction of the stored charge that a battery can deliver depends on multiple factors, including battery chemistry, the rate at which the charge is delivered (current), the required terminal voltage, the storage period, ambient temperature and other factors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The higher the discharge rate, the lower the capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] is the capacity when discharged at a rate of 1 amp.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] is the amount of time (in hours) that a battery can sustain.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Charged batteries (rechargeable or disposable) lose charge by internal self-discharge over time although not discharged, due to the presence of generally irreversible *side reactions* that consume charge carriers without producing current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The rate of self-discharge depends upon battery chemistry and construction, typically from months to years for significant loss.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] When batteries are recharged, additional side reactions reduce capacity for subsequent discharges.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] After enough recharges, in essence all capacity is lost and the battery stops producing power.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Internal energy losses and limitations on the rate that ions pass through the electrolyte cause battery efficiency to vary.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Above a minimum threshold, discharging at a low rate delivers more of the battery's capacity than at a higher rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Installing batteries with varying A·h ratings changes operating time, but not device operation unless load limits are exceeded.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] High-drain loads such as digital cameras can reduce total capacity of rechargeable or disposable batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 2 A·h for a 10- or 20-hour discharge would not sustain a current of 1 A for a full two hours as its stated capacity suggests.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The C-rate is a measure of the rate at which a battery is being charged or discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] It is defined as the current through the battery divided by the theoretical current draw under which the battery would deliver its nominal rated capacity in one hour.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance loss and the chemical processes inside the cells, a battery rarely delivers nameplate rated capacity in only one hour.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Typically, maximum capacity is found at a low C-rate, and charging or discharging at a higher C-rate reduces the usable life and capacity of a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Manufacturers often publish datasheets with graphs showing capacity versus C-rate curves.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] C-rate is also used as a rating on batteries to indicate the maximum current that a battery can safely deliver in a circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Standards for rechargeable batteries generally rate the capacity and charge cycles over a 4-hour (0.25C), 8 hour (0.125C) or longer discharge time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Types intended for special purposes, such as in a computer uninterruptible power supply, may be rated by manufacturers for discharge periods much less than one hour (1C) but may suffer from limited cycle life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In 2009 experimental lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4) battery technology provided the fastest charging and energy delivery, discharging all its energy into a load in 10 to 20 seconds.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In 2024 a prototype battery for electric cars that could charge from 10% to 80% in five minutes was demonstrated, and a Chinese company claimed that car batteries it had introduced charged 10% to 80% in 10.5 minutes—the fastest batteries available—compared to Tesla's 15 minutes to half-charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Battery life (or lifetime) has two meanings for rechargeable batteries but only one for non-chargeable batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] It can be used to describe the length of time a device can run on a fully charged battery—this is also unambiguously termed "endurance".
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] For a rechargeable battery it may also be used for the number of charge/discharge cycles possible before the cells fail to operate satisfactorily—this is also termed "lifespan".
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The term *shelf life* is used to describe how long a battery will retain its performance between manufacture and use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Available capacity of all batteries drops with decreasing temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In contrast to most of today's batteries, the Zamboni pile, invented in 1812, offers a very long service life without refurbishment or recharge, although it can supply very little current (nanoamps).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The Oxford Electric Bell has been ringing almost continuously since 1840 on its original pair of batteries, thought to be Zamboni piles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Disposable batteries typically lose 8–20% of their original charge per year when stored at room temperature (20–30 °C).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] This is known as the "self-discharge" rate, and is due to non-current-producing "side" chemical reactions that occur within the cell even when no load is applied.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The rate of side reactions is reduced for batteries stored at lower temperatures, although some can be damaged by freezing and storing in a fridge will not meaningfully prolong shelf life and risks damaging condensation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Old rechargeable batteries self-discharge more rapidly than disposable alkaline batteries, especially nickel-based batteries; a freshly charged nickel cadmium (NiCd) battery loses 10% of its charge in the first 24 hours, and thereafter discharges at a rate of about 10% a month.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] However, newer low self-discharge nickel–metal hydride (NiMH) batteries and modern lithium designs display a lower self-discharge rate (but still higher than for primary batteries).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The active material on the battery plates changes chemical composition on each charge and discharge cycle; active material may be lost due to physical changes of volume, further limiting the number of times the battery can be recharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Most nickel-based batteries are partially discharged when purchased, and must be charged before first use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Newer NiMH batteries are ready to be used when purchased, and have only 15% discharge in a year.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Some deterioration occurs on each charge–discharge cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Degradation usually occurs because electrolyte migrates away from the electrodes or because active material detaches from the electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Low-capacity NiMH batteries (1,700–2,000 mA·h) can be charged some 1,000 times, whereas high-capacity NiMH batteries (above 2,500 mA·h) last about 500 cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] NiCd batteries tend to be rated for 1,000 cycles before their internal resistance permanently increases beyond usable values.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Fast charging increases component changes, shortening battery lifespan.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] If a charger cannot detect when the battery is fully charged then overcharging is likely, damaging it.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] NiCd cells, if used in a particular repetitive manner, may show a decrease in capacity called "memory effect".
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The effect can be avoided with simple practices.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] NiMH cells, although similar in chemistry, suffer less from memory effect.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Automotive lead–acid rechargeable batteries must endure stress due to vibration, shock, and temperature range.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Because of these stresses and sulfation of their lead plates, few automotive batteries last beyond six years of regular use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Automotive starting (SLI: *Starting, Lighting, Ignition*) batteries have many thin plates to maximize current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In general, the thicker the plates the longer the life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] They are typically discharged only slightly before recharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] "Deep-cycle" lead–acid batteries such as those used in electric golf carts have much thicker plates to extend longevity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The main benefit of the lead–acid battery is its low cost; its main drawbacks are large size and weight for a given capacity and voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries should never be discharged to below 20% of their capacity, because internal resistance will cause heat and damage when they are recharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Deep-cycle lead–acid systems often use a low-charge warning light or a low-charge power cut-off switch to prevent the type of damage that will shorten the battery's life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Battery life can be extended by storing the batteries at a low temperature, as in a refrigerator or freezer, which slows the side reactions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Such storage can extend the life of alkaline batteries by about 5%; rechargeable batteries can hold their charge much longer, depending upon type.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] To reach their maximum voltage, batteries must be returned to room temperature; discharging an alkaline battery at 250 mA at 0 °C is only half as efficient as at 20 °C.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Alkaline battery manufacturers such as Duracell do not recommend refrigerating batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] A battery explosion is generally caused by misuse or malfunction, such as attempting to recharge a primary (non-rechargeable) battery, or a short circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] When a battery is recharged at an excessive rate, an explosive gas mixture of hydrogen and oxygen may be produced faster than it can escape from within the battery (e.g. through a built-in vent), leading to pressure build-up and eventual bursting of the battery case.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In extreme cases, battery chemicals may spray violently from the casing and cause injury.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] An expert summary of the problem indicates that this type uses "liquid electrolytes to transport lithium ions between the anode and the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] If a battery cell is charged too quickly, it can cause a short circuit, leading to explosions and fires".
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Car batteries are most likely to explode when a short circuit generates very large currents.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Such batteries produce hydrogen, which is very explosive, when they are overcharged (because of electrolysis of the water in the electrolyte).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] During normal use, the amount of overcharging is usually very small and generates little hydrogen, which dissipates quickly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] However, when "jump starting" a car, the high current can cause the rapid release of large volumes of hydrogen, which can be ignited explosively by a nearby spark, e.g. when disconnecting a jumper cable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Overcharging (attempting to charge a battery beyond its electrical capacity) can also lead to a battery explosion, in addition to leakage or irreversible damage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] It may also cause damage to the charger or device in which the overcharged battery is later used.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Disposing of a battery via incineration may cause an explosion as steam builds up within the sealed case.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Many battery chemicals are corrosive, poisonous or both.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] If leakage occurs, either spontaneously or through accident, the chemicals released may be dangerous.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] For example, disposable batteries often use a zinc "can" both as a reactant and as the container to hold the other reagents.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] If this kind of battery is over-discharged, the reagents can emerge through the cardboard and plastic that form the remainder of the container.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The active chemical leakage can then damage or disable the equipment that the batteries power.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] For this reason, many electronic device manufacturers recommend removing the batteries from devices that will not be used for extended periods of time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Many types of batteries employ toxic materials such as lead, mercury, and cadmium as an electrode or electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] When each battery reaches end of life it must be disposed of to prevent environmental damage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries are one form of electronic waste (e-waste).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] E-waste recycling services recover toxic substances, which can then be used for new batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Of the nearly three billion batteries purchased annually in the United States, about 179,000 tons end up in landfills across the country.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries may be harmful or fatal if swallowed.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Small button cells can be swallowed, in particular by young children.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] While in the digestive tract, the battery's electrical discharge may lead to tissue damage; such damage is occasionally serious and can lead to death.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Ingested disk batteries do not usually cause problems unless they become lodged in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The most common place for disk batteries to become lodged is the esophagus, resulting in clinical sequelae.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Batteries that successfully traverse the esophagus are unlikely to lodge elsewhere.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The likelihood that a disk battery will lodge in the esophagus is a function of the patient's age and the size of the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Older children do not have problems with batteries smaller than 21–23 mm.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Liquefaction necrosis may occur because sodium hydroxide is generated by the current produced by the battery (usually at the anode).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Perforation has occurred as rapidly as 6 hours after ingestion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Some manufacturers add a bittering agent to their batteries to discourage swallowing.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] Legislation around electric batteries includes such topics as safe disposal and recycling.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In response to reported accidents and failures, occasionally ignition or explosion, recalls of devices using lithium-ion batteries have become more common in recent years.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In the United States, the Mercury-Containing and Rechargeable Battery Management Act of 1996 banned the sale of mercury-containing batteries, enacted uniform labeling requirements for rechargeable batteries and required that rechargeable batteries be easily removable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] California and New York City prohibit the disposal of rechargeable batteries in solid waste.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The rechargeable battery industry operates nationwide recycling programs in the United States and Canada, with dropoff points at local retailers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] The Battery Directive of the European Union has similar requirements, in addition to requiring increased recycling of batteries and promoting research on improved battery recycling methods.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] In accordance with this directive all batteries to be sold within the EU must be marked with the "collection symbol" (a crossed-out wheeled bin).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] This must cover at least 3% of the surface of prismatic batteries and 1.5% of the surface of cylindrical batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-electricity] On 9 December 2022, the European Parliament reached an agreement to force, from 2026, manufacturers to design all electrical appliances sold in the EU (and not used predominantly in wet conditions) so that consumers can easily remove and replace batteries themselves.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] A **battery pack** is a set of any number of (preferably) identical batteries or individual battery cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] They may be configured in a series, parallel or a mixture of both to deliver the desired voltage and current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The term *battery pack* is often used in reference to cordless tools, radio-controlled hobby toys, and battery electric vehicles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Components of battery packs include the individual batteries or cells, and the interconnects which provide electrical conductivity between them.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Rechargeable battery packs often contain voltage and temperature sensors, which the battery charger uses to detect the end of charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Interconnects are also found in batteries as they are the part which connects each cell, though batteries are most often only arranged in series strings.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] When a pack contains groups of cells in parallel there are differing wiring configurations which take into consideration the electrical *balance* of the circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Battery Management System are sometimes used for balancing cells in order to keep their voltages below a maximum value during charging so as to allow the weaker batteries to become fully charged, bringing the whole pack back into balance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Active balancing can also be performed by battery balancer devices which can shuttle energy from strong cells to weaker ones in real time for better balance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] A well-balanced pack lasts longer and delivers better performance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] For an inline package, cells are selected and stacked with solder in between them.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The cells are pressed together and a current pulse generates heat to solder them together and to weld all connections internal to the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] SOC, or state of charge, is the equivalent of a fuel quantity remaining.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] SOC cannot be determined by a simple voltage measurement, because the terminal voltage of a battery may stay substantially constant until it is completely discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] In some types of battery, electrolyte specific gravity may be related to state of charge but this is not measurable on typical battery pack cells, and is not related to state of charge on most battery types.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Most SOC methods take into account voltage and current as well as temperature and other aspects of the discharge and charge process to in essence count up or down within a pre-defined capacity of a pack.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] More complex state of charge estimation systems take into account the Peukert effect which relates the capacity of the battery to the discharge rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] An advantage of a battery pack is the ease with which it can be swapped into or out of a device.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] This allows multiple packs to deliver extended runtimes, freeing up the device for continued use while charging the removed pack separately.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Another advantage is the flexibility of their design and implementation, allowing the use of cheaper high-production cells or batteries to be combined into a pack for nearly any application.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] At the end of product life, batteries can be removed and recycled separately, reducing the total volume of hazardous waste.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Packs are often simpler for end users to repair or tamper with than a sealed non-serviceable battery or cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Though some might consider this an advantage it is important to take safety precautions when servicing a battery pack as they pose a danger as potential chemical, electrical, and fire risks.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] A power bank is a portable device consisting of a battery, a charger to interface battery with charging power source and an output interface to provide desired output voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Power banks are made in various sizes and typically based on lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] A power bank contains battery cells and a voltage converter circuitry.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The internal DC-DC converter manages battery charging and converts the battery stack's voltage to the desired output voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The advertised capacity on the product in many instances is based on the capacity of the internal cells, however the theoretical mAh available to output depends on the output voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The conversion circuit has some energy losses, so the actual output is less than theoretical.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The theoretical mAh of a 3.7 V battery power bank with 5 V output is 74% of the battery mAh rating.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The RavPower RP-PB41 with advertised capacity of 26,800 mAh that was evaluated in the journal has a theoretical capacity of 19,832 mAh, although the delivered capacity was 15,682 mAh, 78% of theoretical value.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Authors attributed the difference to internal resistance in battery and converter losses.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The circuit board can contain additional features such as over discharge protection, automatic shut off and charge level indication LEDs.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Power banks may be able to detect a connection and power on automatically.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] If the current load is under a model-specific threshold for a specific duration, a power bank may power down automatically.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The average power bank in 2023 transferred around 2/3, or 67% of the power bank's battery energy into the battery of the device being charged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Battery cases are small power banks attached to the rear side of a mobile phone like a case.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Power may be delivered through the USB charging ports, or wirelessly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Battery cases also exist in the form of a camera grip accessory, as was for the Nokia Lumia 1020.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] For mobile phones with removable rear cover, *extended batteries* exist.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] These are larger internal batteries attached with a dedicated, more spacious rear cover replacing the default one.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] A disadvantage is incompatibility with other phone cases while attached.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Prong cases included fold-out prongs integrated into the case itself.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] In some parts of the world, there are kiosk based power bank rental or subscription services.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Customers pay for the use of power bank for a specified period of time and return the depleted power bank to the kiosk.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] In one case with a brand called FuelRod, it was sold at an elevated price at various amusement parks with the understanding that they get a perk of free exchange at participating locations.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] FuelRod moved to discontinue the free exchange in 2019 and resulted in a class-action lawsuit reaching a settlement that early adopters would be grandfathered to free exchange privileges.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Per US Federal Aviation Administration regulations, power banks in the United States are not allowed in checked-in luggage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] Power banks up to 100 Wh are allowed as carry-on and those 101 Wh to 160 Wh are allowed with airline approval.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] After Air Busan Flight 391 in Korea, concerns about power banks on flights arose, and new regulations of power banks were issued.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The Korean government issued a ban on using power banks on Korean flights.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] In March 2025, Civil Aviation Authority of Malaysia issued a directive to advise passengers storing power banks on their person, and avoid in overhead bins.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] In February 2025, Eva Air announced their ban on using power banks on flights.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] AirAsia, China Airlines, Starlux Airlines, Singapore Airlines, and Thai Airways issued similar bans later.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] In June, China's Civil Aviation Administration banned passengers from carrying power banks that lack China Compulsory Certification on domestic flights.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/battery-pack] The International Civil Aviation Organization published the new guidelines for power banks on 27 March 2026, which limited to two per passenger, and recharging during the flights is prohibited.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In physics, **energy density** is the quotient between the amount of energy stored in a given system or contained in a given region of space and the volume of the system or region considered.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Often only the *useful* or extractable energy is measured.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] It is sometimes confused with stored energy per unit mass, which is called *specific energy* or *gravimetric energy density*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] There are different types of energy stored, corresponding to a particular type of reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In order of the typical magnitude of the energy stored, examples of reactions are: nuclear, chemical (including electrochemical), electrical, pressure, material deformation or in electromagnetic fields.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Nuclear reactions take place in stars and nuclear power plants, both of which derive energy from the binding energy of nuclei.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Chemical reactions are used by organisms to derive energy from food and by automobiles from the combustion of gasoline.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Liquid hydrocarbons (fuels such as gasoline, diesel and kerosene) are today the densest way known to economically store and transport chemical energy at a large scale (1 kg of diesel fuel burns with the oxygen contained in ≈ 15 kg of air).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Burning local biomass fuels supplies household energy needs (cooking fires, oil lamps, etc.) worldwide.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Electrochemical reactions are used by devices such as laptop computers and mobile phones to release energy from batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Energy per unit volume has the same physical units as pressure, and in many situations is synonymous.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] For example, the energy density of a magnetic field may be expressed as and behaves like a physical pressure.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The energy required to compress a gas to a certain volume may be determined by multiplying the difference between the gas pressure and the external pressure by the change in volume.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] A pressure gradient describes the potential to perform work on the surroundings by converting internal energy to work until equilibrium is reached.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In cosmological and other contexts in general relativity, the energy densities considered relate to the elements of the stress–energy tensor and therefore do include the rest mass energy as well as energy densities associated with pressure.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] When discussing the chemical energy contained, there are different types which can be quantified depending on the intended purpose.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] One is the theoretical total amount of thermodynamic work that can be derived from a system, at a given temperature and pressure imposed by the surroundings, called exergy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Another is the theoretical amount of electrical energy that can be derived from reactants that are at room temperature and atmospheric pressure.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] This is given by the change in standard Gibbs free energy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] But as a source of heat or for use in a heat engine, the relevant quantity is the change in standard enthalpy or the heat of combustion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] A convenient table of HHV and LHV of some fuels can be found in the references.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] For energy storage, the energy density relates the stored energy to the volume of the storage equipment, e.g. the fuel tank.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The higher the energy density of the fuel, the more energy may be stored or transported for the same amount of volume.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The energy of a fuel per unit mass is called its specific energy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The adjacent figure shows the gravimetric and volumetric energy density of some fuels and storage technologies (modified from the Gasoline article).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Some values may not be precise because of isomers or other irregularities.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The heating values of the fuel describe their specific energies more comprehensively.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The density values for chemical fuels do not include the weight of the oxygen required for combustion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The atomic weights of carbon and oxygen are similar, while hydrogen is much lighter.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Figures are presented in this way for those fuels where in practice air would only be drawn in locally to the burner.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] This explains the apparently lower energy density of materials that contain their own oxidizer (such as gunpowder and TNT), where the mass of the oxidizer in effect adds weight, and absorbs some of the energy of combustion to dissociate and liberate oxygen to continue the reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] This also explains some apparent anomalies, such as the energy density of a sandwich appearing to be higher than that of a stick of dynamite.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Given the high energy density of gasoline, the exploration of alternative media to store the energy of powering a car, such as hydrogen or battery, is strongly limited by the energy density of the alternative medium.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The same mass of lithium-ion storage, for example, would result in a car with only 2% the range of its gasoline counterpart.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] If sacrificing the range is undesirable, much more storage volume is necessary.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Alternative options are discussed for energy storage to increase energy density and decrease charging time, such as supercapacitors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] No single energy storage method boasts the best in specific power, specific energy, and energy density.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Peukert's law describes how the amount of useful energy that can be obtained (for a lead-acid cell) depends on how quickly it is pulled out.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In general an engine will generate less kinetic energy due to inefficiencies and thermodynamic considerations—hence the specific fuel consumption of an engine will always be greater than its rate of production of the kinetic energy of motion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Energy density differs from energy conversion efficiency (net output per input) or embodied energy (the energy output costs to provide, as harvesting, refining, distributing, and dealing with pollution all use energy).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Large scale, intensive energy use impacts and is impacted by climate, waste storage, and environmental consequences.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The greatest energy source by far is matter itself, according to the mass–energy equivalence.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] This energy is described by *E* = *mc*2, where *c* is the speed of light.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In terms of density, *m* = *ρV*, where *ρ* is the volumetric mass density, *V* is the volume occupied by the mass.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] This energy can be released by the processes of nuclear fission (~ 0.1%), nuclear fusion (~ 1%), or the annihilation of some or all of the matter in the volume *V* by matter–antimatter collisions (100%).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The most effective ways of accessing this energy, aside from antimatter, are fusion and fission.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Fusion is the process by which the sun produces energy which will be available for billions of years (in the form of sunlight and heat).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] However, as of 2026, sustained fusion power production continues to be elusive.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Nuclear fuels typically have volumetric energy densities at least tens of thousands of times higher than chemical fuels.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] A 1 inch tall uranium fuel pellet is equivalent to about 1 ton of coal, 120 gallons of crude oil, or 17,000 cubic feet of natural gas.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In light-water reactors, 1 kg of natural uranium—following a corresponding enrichment and used for power generation—is equivalent to the energy content of nearly 10,000 kg of mineral oil or 14,000 kg of coal.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Comparatively, coal, gas, and petroleum are the current primary energy sources in the U.S. but have a much lower energy density.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] This represents a considerable density of energy that requires a continuous water flow at high velocity at all times in order to remove heat from the core, even after an emergency shutdown of the reactor.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The incapacity to cool the cores of three BWRs at Fukushima after the 2011 tsunami and the resulting loss of external electrical power and cold source caused the meltdown of the three cores in only a few hours, even though the three reactors were correctly shut down just after the Tōhoku earthquake.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Because antimatter–matter interactions result in complete conversion of the rest mass to radiant energy, the energy density of this reaction depends on the density of the matter and antimatter used.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] A neutron star would approximate the most dense system capable of matter-antimatter annihilation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] A black hole, although denser than a neutron star, does not have an equivalent anti-particle form, but would offer the same 100% conversion rate of mass to energy in the form of Hawking radiation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Even in the case of relatively small black holes (smaller than astronomical objects) the power output would be tremendous.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Electric and magnetic fields can store energy and its density relates to the strength of the fields within a given volume.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] This (volumetric) energy density is given by $u={\frac {\varepsilon }{2}}\mathbf {E} ^{2}+{\frac {1}{2\mu }}\mathbf {B} ^{2}$ where **E** is the electric field, **B** is the magnetic field, and ε and µ are the permittivity and permeability of the surroundings respectively.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The SI unit is the joule per cubic metre.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In ideal (linear and nondispersive) substances, the energy density is $u={\frac {1}{2}}(\mathbf {E} \cdot \mathbf {D} +\mathbf {H} \cdot \mathbf {B} )$ where **D** is the electric displacement field and **H** is the magnetizing field.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In the case of absence of magnetic fields, by exploiting Fröhlich's relationships it is also possible to extend these equations to anisotropic and nonlinear dielectrics, as well as to calculate the correlated Helmholtz free energy and entropy densities.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] In the context of magnetohydrodynamics, the physics of conductive fluids, the magnetic energy density behaves like an additional pressure that adds to the gas pressure of a plasma.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] When a pulsed laser impacts a surface, the radiant exposure, i.e. the energy deposited per unit of surface, may also be called **energy density** or fluence.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The following unit conversions may be helpful when considering the data in the tables: 3.6 MJ = 1 kW⋅h ≈ 1.34 hp⋅h.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] Unless otherwise stated, the values in the following table are lower heating values for perfect combustion, not counting oxidizer mass or volume.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] When used to produce electricity in a fuel cell or to do work, it is the Gibbs free energy of reaction (Δ*G*) that sets the theoretical upper limit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] If the produced H2O is vapor, this is generally greater than the lower heat of combustion, whereas if the produced H 2O is liquid, it is generally less than the higher heat of combustion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] But in the most relevant case of hydrogen, Δ*G* is 113 MJ/kg if water vapor is produced, and 118 MJ/kg if liquid water is produced, both being less than the lower heat of combustion (120 MJ/kg).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The mechanical energy storage capacity, or resilience, of a Hookean material when it is deformed to the point of failure can be computed by calculating tensile strength times the maximum elongation dividing by two.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/energy-density] The maximum elongation of a Hookean material can be computed by dividing stiffness of that material by its ultimate tensile strength.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The **lead–acid battery** is a type of rechargeable battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] First invented in 1859 by French physicist Gaston Planté, it was the first type of rechargeable battery ever created.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Compared to the more modern rechargeable batteries, lead–acid batteries have relatively low energy density and heavier weight.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Despite this, they are able to supply high surge currents.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] These features, along with their low cost, make them useful for motor vehicles in order to provide the high current required by starter motors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] As they are not as expensive when compared to newer technologies, lead–acid batteries are widely used even when surge current is not important and other designs could provide higher energy densities.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In 1999, lead–acid battery sales accounted for 40–50% of the value from batteries sold worldwide (excluding China and Russia), equivalent to a manufacturing market value of about US$15 billion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Large-format lead–acid designs are widely used for storage in backup power supplies in telecommunications networks such as for cell sites, high-availability emergency power systems as used in hospitals, and stand-alone power systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] For these roles, modified versions of the standard cell may be used to improve storage times and reduce maintenance requirements.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] *Gel cell* and *absorbed glass mat* batteries are common in these roles, collectively known as *valve-regulated lead–acid* (*VRLA*) *batteries*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] When charged, the battery's chemical energy is stored in the potential difference between metallic lead at the negative side and lead dioxide on the positive side.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The French scientist Nicolas Gautherot observed in 1801 that wires that had been used for electrolysis experiments would themselves provide a small amount of *secondary* current after the main battery had been disconnected.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In 1859, Gaston Planté's lead–acid battery was the first battery that could be recharged by passing a reverse current through it.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Planté's first model consisted of two lead sheets separated by rubber strips and rolled into a spiral and immersed in a solution containing about 10 percent sulfuric acid.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] His batteries were first used to power the lights in train carriages while stopped at a station.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In 1881, Camille Alphonse Faure invented an improved version that consisted of a lead grid lattice into which a lead oxide paste was pressed, forming a plate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] An early manufacturer (from 1886) of lead–acid batteries was Henri Tudor.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Using a gel electrolyte instead of a liquid allows the battery to be used in different positions without leaking.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Gel electrolyte batteries for any position were first used in the late 1920s, and in the 1930s, portable suitcase radio sets allowed the cell to be mounted vertically or horizontally (but not inverted) due to valve design.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In the 1970s, the *valve-regulated lead–acid* (*VRLA*), or *sealed*, battery was developed, including modern *absorbed glass mat* (*AGM*) types, allowing operation in any position.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] It was discovered early in 2011 that lead–acid batteries do in fact use some aspects of relativity to function, and to a lesser degree, liquid metal and molten-salt batteries such as the Ca-Sb and Sn-Bi also use this effect.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In the discharged state, both the positive and negative plates become lead(II) sulfate (PbSO 4), and the electrolyte loses much of its dissolved sulfuric acid and becomes primarily water.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The release of two conduction electrons gives the lead electrode a negative charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] As electrons accumulate, they create an electric field that attracts hydrogen ions and repels sulfate ions, leading to a double layer near the surface.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The hydrogen ions screen the charged electrode from the solution, which limits further reaction unless charge is allowed to flow out of the electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] taking advantage of the metallic conductivity of PbO 2.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The net energy released per mole (207 g) of Pb(s) converted to PbSO 4(s) is approximately 400 kJ, corresponding to the formation of 36 g of water.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The sum of the molecular masses of the reactants is 642.6 g/mole, so theoretically a cell can produce two faradays of charge (192,971 coulombs) from 642.6 g of reactants, or 83.4 ampere-hours per kilogram for a 2-volt cell (or 13.9 ampere-hours per kilogram for a 12-volt battery).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This comes to 167 watt-hours per kilogram of reactants, but in practice, a lead–acid cell gives only 30–40 watt-hours per kilogram of battery, due to the mass of the water and other constituent part.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In the fully charged state, the negative plate consists of lead and the positive plate is lead dioxide.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The electrolyte solution has a higher concentration of aqueous sulfuric acid, which stores most of the chemical energy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Overcharging with high charging voltages generates oxygen and hydrogen gas by electrolysis of water, which bubbles out and is lost.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The design of some types of lead–acid battery (e.g., "flooded", but not VRLA (AGM or gel)) allows the electrolyte level to be inspected and topped up with pure water to replace any that has been lost in this way.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Because of freezing-point depression, the electrolyte is more likely to freeze in a cold environment when the battery has a low charge and a correspondingly low sulfuric acid concentration.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] During discharge, H+ produced at the negative plates moves into the electrolyte solution and is then consumed at the positive plates, while HSO− 4 is consumed at both plates.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This motion can be electrically-driven proton flow (the Grotthuss mechanism), or by diffusion through the medium, or by the flow of a liquid electrolyte medium.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Since the electrolyte density is greater when the sulfuric acid concentration is higher, the liquid will tend to circulate by convection.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Therefore, a liquid-medium cell tends to rapidly discharge and rapidly charge more efficiently than an otherwise-similar gel cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Some battery designs include a simple hydrometer using colored floating balls of differing density.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] When used in diesel-electric submarines, the specific gravity was regularly measured and written on a blackboard in the control room to indicate how much longer the boat could remain submerged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The battery's open-circuit voltage can also be used to gauge the state of charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] If the connections to the individual cells are accessible, then the state of charge of each cell can be determined which can provide a guide as to the state of health of the battery as a whole; otherwise, the overall battery voltage may be assessed.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] IUoU battery charging is a three-stage charging procedure for lead–acid batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] A lead–acid battery's nominal voltage is 2.1 V for each cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] For a single cell, the voltage can range from 1.8 V loaded at full discharge, to 2.10 V in an open circuit at full charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Float voltage varies depending on battery type (flooded cells, gelled electrolyte, absorbed glass mat), and ranges from 1.8 V to 2.27 V.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Equalization voltage, and charging voltage for sulfated cells, can range from 2.67 V to almost 3 V (only until a charge current is flowing).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Specific values for a given battery depend on the design and manufacturer recommendations, and are usually given at a baseline temperature of 20 °C (68 °F), requiring adjustment for ambient conditions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] IEEE Standard 485-2020 (first published in 1997) is the industry's recommended practice for sizing lead–acid batteries in stationary applications.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The lead–acid cell can be demonstrated using sheet lead plates for the two electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] However, such a construction produces only around one ampere for roughly postcard-sized plates, and for only a few minutes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Gaston Planté found a way to provide a much larger effective surface area.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In Planté's design, the positive and negative plates were formed of two spirals of lead foil, separated with a sheet of cloth and coiled up.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The cells initially had low capacity, so a slow process of *forming* was required to corrode the lead foils, creating lead dioxide on the plates and roughening them to increase surface area.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Initially, this process used electricity from primary batteries; when generators became available after 1870, the cost of producing batteries greatly declined.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Planté plates are still used in some stationary applications, where the plates are mechanically grooved to increase their surface area.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In 1880, Camille Alphonse Faure patented a method of coating a lead grid (which serves as the current conductor) with a paste of lead oxides, sulfuric acid, and water, followed by curing phase in which the plates were exposed to gentle heat in a high-humidity environment.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The curing process changed the paste into a mixture of lead sulfates which adhered to the lead plate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Then, during the battery's initial charge (called *formation*), the cured paste on the plates was converted into electrochemically active material (the *active mass*).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Faure's process significantly reduced the time and cost to manufacture lead–acid batteries, and gave a substantial increase in capacity compared with Planté's battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Faure's method is still in use today, with only incremental improvements to paste composition, curing (which is still done with steam, but is now a very tightly controlled process), and structure and composition of the grid to which the paste is applied.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The grid developed by Faure was of pure lead with connecting rods of lead at right angles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In contrast, present-day grids are structured for improved mechanical strength and improved current flow.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In addition to different grid patterns (ideally, all points on the plate are equidistant from the power conductor), modern-day processes also apply one or two thin fiberglass mats over the grid to distribute the weight more evenly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] And while Faure had used pure lead for his grids, within a year (1881) these had been superseded by lead–antimony (8–12%) alloys to give the structures additional rigidity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] However, high-antimony grids have higher hydrogen evolution (which also accelerates as the battery ages), and thus greater outgassing and higher maintenance costs.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Haring at Bell Labs in the 1930s and eventually led to the development of lead–calcium grid alloys in 1935 for standby power batteries on the U.S. telephone network.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Related research led to the development of lead–selenium grid alloys in Europe a few years later.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Both lead–calcium and lead–selenium grid alloys still add antimony, albeit in much smaller quantities than the older high-antimony grids: lead–calcium grids have 4–6% antimony while lead–selenium grids have 1–2%.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] These metallurgical improvements give the grid more strength, which allows it to carry more weight, and therefore more active material, and so the plates can be thicker, which in turn contributes to battery lifespan since there is more material available to shed before the battery becomes unusable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] High-antimony alloy grids are still used in batteries intended for frequent cycling, e.g. in motor-starting applications where frequent expansion/contraction of the plates need to be compensated for, but where outgassing is not significant since charge currents remain low.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Since the 1950s, batteries designed for infrequent cycling applications (e.g., standby power batteries) increasingly have lead–calcium or lead–selenium alloy grids since these have less hydrogen evolution and thus lower maintenance overhead.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The open-circuit effect is a dramatic loss of battery cycle life, which was observed when calcium was substituted for antimony.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] It is also known as the antimony free effect.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Modern-day paste contains carbon black, *blanc fixe* (barium sulfate), and lignosulfonate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The blanc fixe acts as a seed crystal for the lead–to–lead-sulfate reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The blanc fixe must be fully dispersed in the paste in order for it to be effective.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The lignosulfonate prevents the negative plate from forming a solid mass during the discharge cycle, instead enabling the formation of long needle–like dendrites.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The long crystals have more surface area and are easily converted back to the original state on charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Carbon black counteracts the effect of inhibiting formation caused by the lignosulfonates.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Sulfonated naphthalene condensate dispersant is a more effective expander than lignosulfonate and speeds up formation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This dispersant improves the dispersion of barium sulfate in the paste, reduces hydroset time, produces a more breakage-resistant plate, reduces fine lead particles, and thereby improves handling and pasting characteristics.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] It extends battery life by increasing end-of-charge voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Sulfonated naphthalene requires about one-third to one-half the amount of lignosulfonate and is stable to higher temperatures.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Once dry, the plates are stacked with suitable separators and inserted in a cell container.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The alternate plates then constitute alternating positive and negative electrodes, and within the cell are later connected to one another (negative to negative, positive to positive) in parallel.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The separators inhibit the plates from touching each other, which would otherwise constitute a short circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In flooded and gel cells, the separators are insulating rails or studs, formerly of glass or ceramic, and now of plastic.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In AGM cells, the separator is the glass mat itself, and the rack of plates with separators are squeezed together before insertion into the cell; once in the cell, the glass mats expand slightly, effectively locking the plates in place.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In multi-cell batteries, the cells are then connected to one another in series, either through connectors through the cell walls, or by a bridge over the cell walls.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] All intra-cell and inter-cell connections are of the same lead alloy as that used in the grids.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This is necessary to prevent galvanic corrosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Deep-cycle batteries have a different geometry for their positive electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The positive electrode is not a flat plate but a row of lead–oxide cylinders or tubes strung side by side, so their geometry is called *tubular* or *cylindrical*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The advantage of this is an increased surface area in contact with the electrolyte, with higher discharge and charge currents than a flat-plate cell of the same volume and depth-of-charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Tubular-electrode cells have a higher power density than flat-plate cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This makes cylindrical-geometry plates especially suitable for high-current applications with weight or space limitations, such as for forklifts or for starting marine diesel engines.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] However, because cylinders have less active material in the same volume, they also have lower energy densities than otherwise comparable flat-plate cells, and less active material at the electrode also means they have less material available to shed before the cells become unusable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Cylindrical electrodes are also more complicated to manufacture uniformly, which tends to make them more expensive than flat-plate cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] These trade-offs limit the range of applications in which cylindrical batteries are meaningful to situations where there is insufficient space to install higher-capacity (and thus larger) flat-plate units.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] About 60% of the weight of an automotive-type lead–acid battery rated around 60 A·h is lead or internal parts made of lead; the balance is electrolyte, separators, and the case.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] For example, there are approximately 8.7 kilograms (19 lb) of lead in a typical 14.5-kilogram (32 lb) battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Separators between the positive and negative plates prevent short circuits through physical contact, mostly through dendrites (*treeing*), but also through shedding of the active material.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Separators allow the flow of ions between the plates of an electrochemical cell to form a closed circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Glass fiber mat, rubber, and PVC or polyethylene plastic have been used to make separators.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] An effective separator must possess a number of mechanical properties, including permeability, porosity, pore size distribution, specific surface area, mechanical design and strength, electrical resistance, ionic conductivity, and chemical compatibility with the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In service, the separator must have good resistance to acid and oxidation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The area of the separator must be a little larger than the area of the plates to prevent material shorting between the plates.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The separators must remain stable over the battery's operating temperature range.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In the *absorbent glass mat* (*AGM*) design, the separators between the plates are replaced by a glass fibre mat soaked in electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] There is only enough electrolyte in the mat to keep it wet, and if the battery is punctured, the electrolyte will not flow out of the mats.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In a flooded cell, the bubbles of gas float to the top of the battery and are lost to the atmosphere.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This mechanism for the gas produced to recombine and the additional benefit of a semi-saturated cell providing no substantial leakage of electrolyte upon physical puncture of the battery case allows the battery to be completely sealed, which makes them useful in portable devices and similar roles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Additionally, the battery can be installed in any orientation, though if it is installed upside down, then acid may be blown out through the overpressure vent.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] To reduce the water loss rate, calcium is alloyed with the plates; however, gas build-up remains a problem when the battery is deeply or rapidly charged or discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] To prevent over-pressurization of the battery casing, AGM batteries include a one-way blow-off valve, and are often known as *valve-regulated lead–acid* (*VRLA*) designs.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Another advantage to the AGM design is that the electrolyte becomes the separator material and is mechanically strong.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This allows the plate stack to be compressed together in the battery shell, slightly increasing energy density compared to liquid or gel versions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] AGM batteries often show a characteristic bulging in their shells when built in common rectangular shapes, due to the expansion of the positive plates.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The mat also prevents the vertical motion of the electrolyte within the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] When a normal wet cell is stored in a discharged state, the heavier acid molecules tend to settle to the bottom of the battery, causing the electrolyte to stratify.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] When the battery is then used, the majority of the current flows only in this area, and the bottom of the plates tends to wear out rapidly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This is one of the reasons a conventional car battery can be ruined by leaving it stored for a long period and then used and recharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The mat significantly prevents this stratification, eliminating the need to periodically shake the batteries, boil them, or run an *equalization charge* through them to mix the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Stratification also causes the upper layers of the battery to become almost completely water, which can freeze in cold weather; AGMs are significantly less susceptible to damage due to low-temperature use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] While AGM cells do not permit watering (typically it is impossible to add water without drilling a hole in the battery), their recombination process is fundamentally limited by the usual chemical processes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Hydrogen gas will even diffuse right through the plastic case itself.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Some have found that it is profitable to add water to an AGM battery, but this must be done slowly to allow for the water to mix throughout the battery via diffusion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] When a lead–acid battery loses water, its acid concentration increases, increasing the corrosion rate of the plates significantly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] AGM cells already have a high acid content in an attempt to lower the water loss rate and increase standby voltage, and this brings about shorter life compared to a lead–antimony flooded battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] If the open circuit voltage of AGM cells is significantly higher than 2.093 volts, or 12.56 V for a 12 V battery, then it has a higher acid content than a flooded cell; while this is normal for an AGM battery, it is not desirable for long life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] AGM cells that are intentionally or accidentally overcharged will show a higher open-circuit voltage according to the water lost (and acid concentration increased).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] One amp-hour of overcharge will electrolyse 0.335 grams of water per cell; some of this liberated hydrogen and oxygen will recombine, but not all of it.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] During the 1970s, researchers developed the sealed version or gel battery, which mixes a silica gelling agent into the electrolyte (silica-gel-based lead–acid batteries used in portable radios from the early 1930s were not fully sealed).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This converts the formerly liquid interior of the cells into a semi-stiff paste, providing many of the same advantages of the AGM.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Such designs are even less susceptible to evaporation and are often used in situations where little or no periodic maintenance is possible.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Gel cells also have lower freezing and higher boiling points than the liquid electrolytes used in conventional wet cells and AGMs, which makes them suitable for use in extreme conditions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The only downside to the gel design is that the gel prevents rapid motion of the ions in the electrolyte, which reduces carrier mobility and thus surge current capability.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] For this reason, gel cells are most commonly found in energy storage applications like off-grid systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Both gel and AGM designs are sealed, do not require watering, can be used in any orientation, and use a valve for gas blowoff.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] For this reason, both designs can be called maintenance-free, sealed, and VRLA.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] However, it is quite common to find resources stating that these terms refer to one or another of these designs, specifically.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In a valve-regulated lead–acid (VRLA) battery, the hydrogen and oxygen produced in the cells largely recombine into water.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Leakage is minimal, although some electrolyte still escapes if the recombination cannot keep up with gas evolution.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Since VRLA batteries do not require (and make impossible) regular checking of the electrolyte level, they have been called *maintenance-free batteries*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] However, this is somewhat of a misnomer: VRLA cells do require maintenance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] As electrolyte is lost, VRLA cells dry out and lose capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This can be detected by taking regular internal resistance, conductance, or impedance measurements.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Regular testing reveals whether more involved testing and maintenance is required.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Maintenance procedures have recently been developed allowing rehydration, often restoring significant amounts of lost capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] VRLA types became popular on motorcycles around 1983, because the separator improves resistance to vibration and prevents the acid electrolyte from spilling.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] They are also popular in stationary applications such as telecommunications sites, due to their small footprint and installation flexibility.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Most of the world's lead–acid batteries are automobile starting, lighting, and ignition (SLI) batteries, with an estimated 320 million units shipped in 1999.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In 1992 about 3 million tons of lead were used in the manufacture of batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] More recent data shows continued growth, with approximately 150 million units shipped in 2024 across North America.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Wet cell stand-by (stationary) batteries designed for deep discharge are commonly used in large backup power supplies for telephone and computer centres, grid energy storage, and off-grid household electric power systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Lead–acid batteries are used in emergency lighting and to power sump pumps in case of power failure.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Traction (propulsion) batteries are used in golf carts and other battery electric vehicles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Large lead–acid batteries are also used to power the electric motors in diesel–electric (conventional) submarines when submerged, and are used as emergency power on nuclear submarines as well.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Valve-regulated lead–acid batteries cannot spill their electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] They are used in back-up power supplies for alarm and smaller computer systems (particularly in uninterruptible power supplies) and for e-scooters, electric wheelchairs, electrified bicycles, marine applications, battery electric vehicles or micro hybrid vehicles, and motorcycles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Many electric forklifts use lead–acid batteries, where the weight is used as part of a counterweight.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Lead–acid batteries were used to supply the filament (heater) voltage, with 2 V common in early vacuum tube (valve) radio receivers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Portable batteries for miners' cap headlamps typically used to have two or three cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Lead–acid batteries designed for starting automotive engines are not designed for deep discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] They have a large number of thin plates designed for maximum surface area, and therefore maximum current output, which can easily be damaged by deep discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Repeated deep discharges will result in capacity loss and ultimately in premature failure, either as the plates disintegrate due to mechanical stresses or from rapid sulfation when the plates are at low voltages during the deep-cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Starting batteries kept on a continuous float charge might suffer from grid corrosion which can result in failure modes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Starter batteries can therefore be kept open circuit but charged regularly (e.g. once a month) to prevent sulfation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Starting batteries are lighter than deep-cycle batteries of the same size, because the thinner and lighter cell plates do not extend all the way to the bottom of the battery case.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This allows loose, disintegrated material to fall off the plates and collect at the bottom of the cell, prolonging the service life of the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] If this loose debris rises enough, then it may touch the bottom of the plates and cause failure of a cell, resulting in loss of battery voltage and capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] These batteries have thicker plates that cannot deliver as much *peak current* but can withstand frequent discharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Some batteries are designed as a compromise between starter (high-current) and deep cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] They are able to be discharged to a greater degree than automotive batteries, but less so than deep-cycle batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] They may be referred to as *marine*, *motorhome*, or *leisure batteries*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The capacity of a lead–acid battery is not a fixed quantity but varies according to how quickly it is discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The empirical relationship between discharge rate and capacity is known as Peukert's law.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] When a battery is charged or discharged, only the reacting chemicals, which are at the interface between the electrodes and the electrolyte, are initially affected.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] With time, the charge stored in the chemicals at the interface, often called *interface charge* or *surface charge*, spreads by diffusion of these chemicals throughout the volume of the active material.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Consider a battery that has been completely discharged (such as occurs when leaving the car lights on overnight, a current draw of about 6 amps).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] If it then is given a fast charge for only a few minutes, the battery plates charge only near the interface between the plates and the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In this case the battery voltage might rise to a value near that of the charger voltage; this causes the charging current to decrease significantly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] After a few hours this interface charge will spread to the volume of the electrode and electrolyte; this leads to an interface charge so low that it may be insufficient to start the car.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] As long as the charging voltage stays below the gassing voltage (about 14.4 volts in a normal lead–acid battery), battery damage is unlikely, and in time the battery should return to a nominally charged state.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Lead–acid batteries lose the ability to accept a charge when discharged for too long due to *sulfation*, the crystallization of lead sulfate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] They generate electricity through a double sulfate chemical reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Lead and lead dioxide, the active materials on the battery's plates, react with sulfuric acid in the electrolyte to form lead sulfate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The lead sulfate first forms in a finely divided, amorphous state and easily reverts to lead, lead dioxide, and sulfuric acid when the battery recharges.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] As batteries cycle through numerous discharges and charges, some lead sulfate does not recombine into electrolyte and slowly converts into a stable crystalline form that no longer dissolves on recharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Thus, not all the lead is returned to the battery plates, and the amount of usable active material necessary for electricity generation declines over time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Sulfation occurs in lead–acid batteries when they are subjected to insufficient charging during normal operation, it also occurs when lead–acid batteries left unused with incomplete charge for an extended time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] It impedes recharging; sulfate deposits ultimately expand, cracking the plates and destroying the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Eventually, so much of the battery plate area is unable to supply current that the battery capacity is greatly reduced.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In addition, the sulfate portion (of the lead sulfate) is not returned to the electrolyte as sulfuric acid.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] It is believed that large crystals physically block the electrolyte from entering the pores of the plates.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] A white coating on the plates may be visible in batteries with clear cases or after dismantling the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Batteries that are sulfated show a high internal resistance and can deliver only a small fraction of normal discharge current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Sulfation also affects the charging cycle, resulting in longer charging times, less-efficient and incomplete charging, and higher battery temperatures.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, ignition; e.g., car batteries) suffer the most deterioration because vehicles normally stand unused for relatively long periods of time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Deep-cycle and motive power batteries are subjected to regular controlled overcharging, eventually failing due to corrosion of the positive plate grids rather than sulfation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Sulfation can be avoided if the battery is fully recharged immediately after a discharge cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] There are no known independently verified ways to reverse sulfation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] There are commercial products claiming to achieve desulfation through various techniques such as pulse charging, but there are no peer-reviewed publications verifying their claims.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Sulfation prevention remains the best course of action, by periodically fully charging the lead–acid batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] A typical lead–acid battery contains a mixture with varying concentrations of water and acid.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Sulfuric acid has a higher density than water, which causes the acid formed at the plates during charging to flow downward and collect at the bottom of the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Eventually the mixture will again reach uniform composition by diffusion, but this is a very slow process.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Repeated cycles of partial charging and discharging will increase stratification of the electrolyte, reducing the capacity and performance of the battery because the lack of acid on top limits plate activation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The stratification also promotes corrosion on the upper half of the plates and sulfation at the bottom.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Periodic overcharging creates gaseous reaction products at the plate, causing convection currents which mix the electrolyte and resolve the stratification.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Mechanical stirring of the electrolyte would have the same effect.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Batteries in moving vehicles are also subject to sloshing and splashing in the cells, as the vehicle accelerates, brakes, and turns.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Excessive charging causes electrolysis, emitting hydrogen and oxygen in a process known as *gassing*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Wet cells have open vents to release any gas produced, and VRLA batteries rely on valves fitted to each cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Catalytic caps are available for flooded cells to recombine hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] A VRLA cell normally recombines any hydrogen and oxygen produced inside the cell, but malfunction or overheating may cause gas to build up.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] If this happens (for example, on overcharging), then the valve vents the gas and normalizes the pressure, producing a characteristic acidic smell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] However, valves can fail, such as if dirt and debris accumulate, allowing pressure to build up.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Accumulated hydrogen and oxygen sometimes ignite in an internal explosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The force of the explosion can cause the battery's casing to burst, or cause its top to fly off, spraying acid and casing fragments.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] An explosion in one cell may ignite any combustible gas mixture in the remaining cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Similarly, in a poorly ventilated area, connecting or disconnecting a closed circuit (such as a load or a charger) to the battery terminals can also cause sparks and an explosion, if any gas was vented from the cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Individual cells within a battery can also short circuit, causing an explosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The cells of VRLA batteries typically swell when the internal pressure rises, thereby giving a warning to users and mechanics.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The deformation varies from cell to cell, and is greatest at the ends where the walls are unsupported by other cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Such over-pressurized batteries should be carefully isolated and discarded.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Personnel working near batteries at risk of explosion should protect their eyes and exposed skin from burns due to spraying acid and fire by wearing a face shield, overalls, and gloves.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Using goggles instead of a face shield leaves the face exposed to possible flying acid, case or battery fragments, and heat from a potential explosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] According to a 2003 report entitled "Getting the Lead Out", by Environmental Defense and the Ecology Center of Ann Arbor, Michigan, the batteries of vehicles on the road contained an estimated 2,600,000 metric tons (2,600,000 long tons; 2,900,000 short tons) of lead.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Some lead compounds are extremely toxic.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Long-term exposure to even tiny amounts of these compounds can cause brain and kidney damage, hearing impairment, and learning problems in children.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The auto industry uses over 1,000,000 metric tons (980,000 long tons; 1,100,000 short tons) of lead every year, with 90% going to conventional lead–acid vehicle batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] While lead recycling is a well-established industry, more than 40,000 metric tons (39,000 long tons; 44,000 short tons) ends up in landfills every year.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] According to the federal Toxic Release Inventory, another 70,000 metric tons (69,000 long tons; 77,000 short tons) are released in the lead mining and manufacturing process.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Attempts are being made to develop alternatives (particularly for automotive use) because of concerns about the environmental consequences of improper disposal and of lead smelting operations, among other reasons.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Alternatives are unlikely to displace them for applications such as engine starting or backup power systems, since the batteries, although heavy, are inexpensive in up-front cost.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] According to the Battery Council International, an industry group, lead–acid battery recycling is one of the most successful recycling programs in the world.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] In the United States 99% of all battery lead was recycled between 2017 and 2021.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Environmental Protection Administration, confirm that the recycling rate has risen from 76% in 1970, to 99% in modern times.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Lead is highly toxic to humans, and recycling it can result in pollution and contamination of people, resulting in numerous and lasting health problems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] One ranking identifies lead–acid battery recycling as the world's most deadly industrial process, in terms of disability-adjusted life years lost—resulting in 2,000,000 to 4,800,000 estimated years of individual human life lost, globally.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Lead–acid battery-recycling sites have themselves become a source of lead pollution, and by 1992, the EPA had selected 29 such sites for its Superfund clean-up, with 22 on its National Priority List.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] An effective pollution control system is a necessity to prevent lead emission.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Continuous improvement in battery recycling plants and furnace designs is required to keep pace with emission standards for lead smelters.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Voluntary certification programs such as LeadBattery360 aim to drive such improvements.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Chemical additives have been used ever since the lead–acid battery became a commercial item, to reduce lead sulfate buildup on plates and improve battery condition when added to the electrolyte of a vented lead–acid battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Such treatments are rarely, if ever, effective.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Two compounds used for such purposes are Epsom salts and EDTA.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Epsom salts reduce the internal resistance in a weak or damaged battery and may allow a small amount of extended life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] EDTA can be used to dissolve the sulfate deposits of heavily discharged plates.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] However, the dissolved material is then no longer available to participate in the normal charge-discharge cycle, so a battery temporarily revived with EDTA will have a reduced life expectancy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Residual EDTA in the lead–acid cell forms organic acids which will accelerate corrosion of the lead plates and internal connectors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The active materials change physical form during charge/discharge, resulting in growth and distortion of the electrodes, and shedding of electrodes into the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Once the active material has fallen out of the plates, it cannot be restored into position by any chemical treatment.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Similarly, internal physical problems such as cracked plates, corroded connectors, or damaged separators cannot be restored chemically.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Corrosion of the external metal parts of the lead–acid battery results from a chemical reaction of the battery terminals, plugs, and connectors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Corrosion on the positive terminal is caused by electrolysis, due to a mismatch of metal alloys used in the manufacture of the battery terminal and cable connector.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] White corrosion is usually lead or zinc sulfate crystals.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Aluminum connectors corrode to aluminum sulfate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Copper connectors produce blue and white corrosion crystals.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Corrosion of a battery's terminals can be reduced by coating the terminals with petroleum jelly or a commercially available product made for the purpose.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] If the battery is overfilled with water and electrolyte, then thermal expansion can force some of the liquid out of the battery vents onto the top of the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] This solution can then react with the lead and other metals in the battery connector and cause corrosion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] The electrolyte can seep from the plastic-to-lead seal where the battery terminals penetrate the plastic case.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/lead-acid-battery] Acid fumes that vaporize through the vent caps, often caused by overcharging, and insufficient battery box ventilation can allow the sulfuric acid fumes to build up and react with the exposed metals.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] A **nickel–metal hydride battery** (**NiMH** or **Ni–MH**) is a type of rechargeable battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The chemical reaction at the positive electrode is similar to that of the older nickel–cadmium cell (NiCd), with both using nickel oxide hydroxide, NiO(OH).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] However, the negative electrodes use a hydrogen-absorbing alloy instead of cadmium.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH batteries typically have two to three times the capacity of NiCd batteries of the same size, with significantly higher energy density, although only about half that of lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH batteries have almost entirely replaced NiCd.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] These batteries are typically used as a substitute for similarly shaped non-rechargeable alkaline and other primary batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] They provide a cell voltage of about 1.2V while fresh alkaline cells provide 1.5V; however devices designed for alkaline batteries operate until cell voltage gradually drops to around 1.0V, while the voltage of a fully-charged NiMH cell drops more slowly, giving good endurance for a 1.0V end point.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH batteries are less prone to leaking corrosive electrolyte than primary batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Work on NiMH batteries began at the Battelle-Geneva Research Center following the technology's invention in 1967.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] It was based on sintered Ti2Ni+TiNi+x alloys and NiOOH electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Development was sponsored over nearly two decades by Daimler-Benz and by Volkswagen AG within Deutsche Automobilgesellschaft, now a subsidiary of Daimler AG.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The batteries' specific energy reached 50 W·h/kg (180 kJ/kg), specific power up to 1000 W/kg and a life of 500 charge cycles (at 100% depth of discharge).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Patent applications were filed in European countries (priority: Switzerland), the United States, and Japan.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The patents transferred to Daimler-Benz.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Interest grew in the 1970s with the commercialisation of the nickel–hydrogen battery for satellite applications.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Hydride technology promised an alternative, less bulky way to store the hydrogen.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Research carried out by Philips Laboratories and France's CNRS developed new high-energy hybrid alloys incorporating rare-earth metals for the negative electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] However, these suffered from alloy instability in alkaline electrolyte and consequently insufficient cycle life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In 1987, Willems and Buschow demonstrated a successful battery based on this approach (using a mixture of La0.8Nd0.2Ni2.5Co2.4Si0.1), which kept 84% of its charge capacity after 4000 charge-discharge cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] More economically viable alloys using mischmetal instead of lanthanum were soon developed.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Modern NiMH cells were based on this design.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The first consumer-grade NiMH cells became commercially available in 1989.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In 1998, Stanford Ovshinsky at Ovonic Battery Co., which had been working on MH-NiOOH batteries since mid-1980, improved the Ti–Ni alloy structure and composition and patented its innovations.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In 2008, more than two million hybrid cars worldwide were manufactured with NiMH batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In the European Union due to its Battery Directive, nickel–metal hydride batteries replaced Ni–Cd batteries for portable consumer use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In Switzerland in 2009, approximately 60% of portable rechargeable batteries were NiMH.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In 2000, almost half of all portable rechargeable batteries sold in Japan were NiMH, compared to 22% in 2010.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This percentage has fallen over time due to the increase in manufacture of lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In 2015 BASF produced a modified microstructure that helped make NiMH batteries more durable, in turn allowing changes to the cell design that saved considerable weight, allowing the specific energy to reach 140 watt-hours per kilogram.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The reactions proceed left to right during charge and the opposite during discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The metal M in the negative electrode of a NiMH cell is an intermetallic compound.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Many different compounds have been developed for this application, but those in current use fall into two classes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The most common is AB5, where A is a rare-earth mixture of lanthanum, cerium, neodymium, praseodymium, and B is nickel, cobalt, manganese, or aluminium.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Some cells use higher-capacity negative electrode materials based on AB2 compounds, where A is titanium or vanadium, and B is zirconium or nickel, modified with chromium, cobalt, iron, or manganese.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH cells have an alkaline electrolyte, usually potassium hydroxide.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The positive electrode is nickel hydroxide, and the negative electrode is hydrogen in the form of an interstitial metal hydride.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Hydrophilic polyolefin nonwovens are used for separation.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] When fast-charging, it is advisable to charge the NiMH cells with a smart battery charger to avoid overcharging, which can damage cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The simplest of the safe charging methods is with a fixed low current, with or without a timer.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Most manufacturers claim that overcharging is safe at very low currents, below 0.1 *C* (*C*/10) (where *C* is the current equivalent to the capacity of the battery divided by one hour).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The Panasonic NiMH charging manual warns that overcharging for long enough can damage a battery and suggests limiting the total charging time to 10–20 hours.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Duracell suggests that a trickle charge at *C*/300 can be used for batteries that must be kept in a fully charged state.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Some chargers do this after the charge cycle, to offset natural self-discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] A similar approach is suggested by Energizer, which indicates that self-catalysis can recombine gas formed at the electrodes for charge rates up to C/10.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The company recommends *C*/30 or *C*/40 for indefinite applications where long life is important.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This is the approach taken in emergency lighting applications, where the design remains essentially the same as in older NiCd units, except for an increase in the trickle-charging resistor value.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Panasonic's handbook recommends that NiMH batteries on standby be charged by a lower duty cycle approach, where a pulse of a higher current is used whenever the battery's voltage drops below 1.3 V.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This can extend battery life and use less energy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] To prevent cell damage, fast chargers must terminate their charge cycle before overcharging occurs.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] One method is to monitor the change of voltage with time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] When the battery is fully charged, the voltage across its terminals drops slightly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The charger can detect this and stop charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This method is often used with nickel–cadmium cells, which display a large voltage drop at full charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] However, the voltage drop is much less pronounced for NiMH and can be non-existent at low charge rates, which can make the approach unreliable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Another option is to monitor the change of voltage with respect to time and stop when this becomes zero, but this risks premature cutoffs.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] With this method, a much higher charging rate can be used than with a trickle charge, up to 1 *C*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] At this charge rate, Panasonic recommends to terminate charging when the voltage drops 5–10 mV per cell from the peak voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Since this method measures the voltage across the battery, a constant-current (rather than a constant-voltage) charging circuit is used.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The temperature-change method is similar in principle to the Δ*V* method.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Because the charging voltage is nearly constant, constant-current charging delivers energy at a near-constant rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] When the cell is not fully charged, most of this energy is converted to chemical energy.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] However, when the cell reaches full charge, most of the charging energy is converted to heat.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This increases the rate of change of battery temperature, which can be detected by a sensor such as a thermistor.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Both Panasonic and Duracell suggest a maximal rate of temperature increase of 1 °C per minute.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Using a temperature sensor allows an absolute temperature cutoff, which Duracell suggests at 60 °C.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] With both the Δ*T* and the Δ*V* charging methods, both manufacturers recommend a further period of trickle charging to follow the initial rapid charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] A resettable fuse in series with the cell, particularly of the bimetallic strip type, increases safety.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This fuse opens if either the current or the temperature gets too high.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] However, this only works with overcharging currents of up to 0.1 *C* (that is, nominal capacity divided by ten hours).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This reaction causes batteries to heat, ending the charging process.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] A method for very rapid charging called in-cell charge control involves an internal pressure switch in the cell, which disconnects the charging current in the event of overpressure.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] One inherent risk with NiMH chemistry is that overcharging causes hydrogen gas to form, potentially rupturing the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Therefore, cells have a vent to release the gas in the event of serious overcharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH batteries are made of environmentally friendly materials.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The batteries contain only mildly toxic substances and are recyclable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Voltage depression (often mistakenly attributed to the memory effect) from repeated partial discharge can occur, but is reversible with a few full discharge/charge cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] A fully charged cell supplies an average 1.25 V/cell during discharge, declining to about 1.0–1.1 V/cell (further discharge may cause permanent damage in the case of multi-cell packs, due to polarity reversal of the weakest cell).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Under a light load (0.5 amperes), the starting voltage of a freshly charged AA NiMH cell in good condition is about 1.4 volts.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Complete discharge of multi-cell packs can cause reverse polarity in one or more cells, which can permanently damage them.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This situation can occur in the common arrangement of four AA cells in series, where one cell completely discharges before the others due to small differences in capacity among the cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] When this happens, the good cells start to drive the discharged cell into reverse polarity (i.e. positive anode and negative cathode).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Some cameras, GPS receivers and PDAs detect the safe end-of-discharge voltage of the series cells and perform an auto-shutdown, but devices such as flashlights/torches and some toys do not.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Irreversible damage from polarity reversal is a particular danger, even when a low voltage-threshold cutout is employed, when the cells vary in temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This is because capacity significantly declines as the cells are cooled.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This results in a lower voltage under load of the colder cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Historically, NiMH cells have had a somewhat higher self-discharge rate (equivalent to internal leakage) than NiCd cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The self-discharge rate varies greatly with temperature, where lower storage temperature leads to slower discharge and longer battery life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The self-discharge is 5–20% on the first day and stabilizes around 0.5–4% per day at room temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] But at 45 °C (113 °F) it is approximately three times as high.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The **low–self-discharge nickel–metal hydride battery** (**LSD NiMH**) has a significantly lower rate of self-discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The innovation was introduced in 2005 by Sanyo, branded Eneloop.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] By using improvements to electrode separator, positive electrode, and other components, manufacturers claim the cells retain 70–85% of their capacity when stored for one year at 20 °C (68 °F), compared to about half for normal NiMH batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] They are otherwise similar to standard NiMH batteries, and can be charged in standard NiMH chargers.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] These cells are marketed as "hybrid", "ready-to-use" or "pre-charged" rechargeables.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Retention of charge depends in large part on the battery's resistance to leakage (the higher the better), and on its physical size and charge capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Separators keep the two electrodes apart to slow electrical discharge while allowing the transport of ionic charge carriers that close the circuit during the passage of current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] High-quality separators are critical for battery performance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The self-discharge rate depends upon separator thickness; thicker separators reduce self-discharge, but also reduce capacity as they leave less space for active components, and thin separators lead to higher self-discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Some batteries may have overcome this tradeoff by using more precisely manufactured thin separators, and a sulfonated polyolefin separator, an improvement over the hydrophilic polyolefin based on ethylene vinyl alcohol.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Low-self-discharge cells have somewhat lower capacity than otherwise equivalent NiMH cells because of the larger volume of the separator.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The highest-capacity low-self-discharge AA cells have 2500 mAh capacity, compared to 2700 mAh for high-capacity AA NiMH cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Most of these improvements have no or negligible effect on cost; some increase cost modestly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH cells are often used in digital cameras and other high-drain devices, where they outperform primary batteries, usually using alkaline chemistry, but also inferior zinc-carbon and chloride.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH cells are better for high-current-drain applications than alkaline batteries due to their lower internal resistance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Typical alkaline AA-size batteries, which offer approximately 2.6 Ah capacity at low current demand (25 mA), provide only 1.3 Ah capacity with a 500 mA load.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Digital cameras with LCDs and flashlights can draw over 1 A, quickly depleting them.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH cells can deliver these current levels without similar loss of capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Alkaline (and other technologies such as zinc-carbon or chloride) primary (disposable) batteries supply a voltage of 1.5V when fresh but gradually decreasing in use, and devices using them are usually designed to operate up to an end-point voltage of about 1.0V.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Battery-level indicators designed for alkaline batteries are inaccurate with the lower initial voltage but slower decrease of NiMH.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Lithium-ion batteries can deliver extremely high power and have a higher specific energy than nickel–metal hydride batteries, but they were originally significantly more expensive.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] The cost of lithium batteries fell drastically during the 2010s and many small consumer devices now have non-consumer-replaceable lithium batteries as a result.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Lithium batteries produce a higher voltage (3.2–3.7 V nominal), and are thus not a drop-in replacement for AA (alkaline or NiMh) batteries without circuitry to reduce voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Although a single lithium cell will typically provide ideal power to replace 3 NiMH cells, the form factor means that the device still needs modification.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH batteries can easily be made smaller and lighter than lead-acid batteries and have completely replaced them in small devices.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] However, lead-acid batteries can deliver huge current at low cost, making lead-acid batteries more suitable for starter motors in combustion vehicles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] As of 2005, nickel–metal hydride batteries constituted three percent of the battery market.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH batteries have replaced NiCd for many roles, notably small rechargeable batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] NiMH batteries are commonly available in AA (penlight-size) batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] These have nominal charge capacities (*C*) of 1.1–2.8 Ah at 1.2 V, measured at the rate that discharges the cell in 5 hours.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Useful discharge capacity is a decreasing function of the discharge rate, but up to a rate of around 1×*C* (full discharge in 1 hour), it does not differ significantly from the nominal capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Fully charged NiMH batteries nominally operate at 1.2 V per cell, somewhat lower than fresh 1.5 V disposable cells, but most devices are designed to continue operating until the voltage drops to about 1.0V, so NiMH batteries can replace alkaline batteries without loss of performance.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Prior all-electric plug-in vehicles included the General Motors EV1, first-generation Toyota RAV4 EV, Honda EV Plus, Ford Ranger EV and Vectrix scooter.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Every first generation hybrid vehicle used NIMH batteries, most notably the Toyota Prius and Honda Insight, as well as later models including the Ford Escape Hybrid, Chevrolet Malibu Hybrid and Honda Civic Hybrid also use them.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Ovshinsky invented and patented a popular improvement of the NiMH battery and founded Ovonic Battery Company in 1982.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] General Motors purchased Ovonics' patent in 1994.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] By the late 1990s, NiMH batteries were being used successfully in many fully electric vehicles, such as the General Motors EV1 and Dodge Caravan EPIC minivan.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] This generation of electric cars, although successful, was abruptly pulled off the market.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] In October 2000, the patent was sold to Texaco, and a week later Texaco was acquired by Chevron.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Chevron's Cobasys subsidiary provides these batteries only to large OEM orders.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] General Motors shut down production of the EV1, citing lack of battery availability as a chief obstacle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/nickel-metal-hydride-battery] Cobasys control of NiMH batteries created a patent encumbrance for large automotive NiMH batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] It is composed of one or more electrochemical cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The term "accumulator" is used as it accumulates and stores energy through a reversible electrochemical reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Rechargeable batteries are produced in many different shapes and sizes, ranging from button cells to megawatt systems connected to stabilize an electrical distribution network.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Several different combinations of electrode materials and electrolytes are used, including lead–acid, zinc–air, nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), lithium-ion (Li-ion), lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO4), and lithium-ion polymer (Li-ion polymer).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Rechargeable batteries typically initially cost more than disposable batteries but have a much lower total cost of ownership and environmental impact, as they can be recharged inexpensively many times before they need replacing.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Some rechargeable battery types are available in the same sizes and voltages as disposable types, and can be used interchangeably with them.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Billions of dollars in research are being invested around the world for improving batteries as industry focuses on building better batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Emerging applications in hybrid internal combustion-battery and electric vehicles drive the technology to reduce cost, weight, and size, and increase lifetime.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Older rechargeable batteries self-discharge relatively rapidly and require charging before first use; some newer low self-discharge NiMH batteries hold their charge for many months, and are typically sold factory-charged to about 70% of their rated capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Battery storage power stations use rechargeable batteries for load-leveling (storing electric energy at times of low demand for use during peak periods) and for renewable energy uses (such as storing power generated from photovoltaic arrays during the day to be used at night).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Load-leveling reduces the maximum power which a plant must be able to generate, reducing capital cost and the need for peaking power plants.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] According to a report from Research and Markets, the analysts forecast the global rechargeable battery market to grow at a CAGR of 8.32% during the period 2018–2022.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Small rechargeable batteries can power portable electronic devices, power tools, appliances, and so on.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Heavy-duty batteries power electric vehicles, ranging from scooters to locomotives and ships.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] They are used in distributed electricity generation and in stand-alone power systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] During charging, the positive active material is oxidized, releasing electrons, and the negative material is reduced, absorbing electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] These electrons constitute the current flow in the external circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The electrolyte may serve as a simple buffer for internal ion flow between the electrodes, as in lithium-ion and nickel-cadmium cells, or it may be an active participant in the electrochemical reaction, as in lead–acid cells.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The energy used to charge rechargeable batteries usually comes from a battery charger using AC mains electricity, although some are equipped to use a vehicle's 12-volt DC power outlet.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The voltage of the source must be higher than that of the battery to force current to flow into it, but not too much higher or the battery may be damaged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Chargers take from a few minutes to several hours to charge a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Slow "dumb" chargers without voltage or temperature-sensing capabilities will charge at a low rate, typically taking 14 hours or more to reach a full charge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Rapid chargers can typically charge cells in two to five hours, depending on the model, with the fastest taking as little as fifteen minutes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Fast chargers must have multiple ways of detecting when a cell reaches full charge (change in terminal voltage, temperature, etc.) to stop charging before harmful overcharging or overheating occurs.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The fastest chargers often incorporate cooling fans to keep the cells from overheating.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Battery packs intended for rapid charging may include a temperature sensor that the charger uses to protect the pack; the sensor will have one or more additional electrical contacts.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Different battery chemistries require different charging schemes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For example, some battery types can be safely recharged from a constant voltage source.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Other types need to be charged with a regulated current source that tapers as the battery reaches fully charged voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Charging a battery incorrectly can damage a battery; in extreme cases, batteries can overheat, catch fire, or explosively vent their contents.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Battery charging and discharging rates are often discussed by referencing a "C" rate of current.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The C rate is that which would theoretically fully charge or discharge the battery in one hour.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For example, trickle charging might be performed at C/20 (or a "20-hour" rate), while typical charging and discharging may occur at C/2 (two hours for full capacity).
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The available capacity of electrochemical cells varies depending on the discharge rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Some energy is lost in the internal resistance of cell components (plates, electrolyte, interconnections), and the rate of discharge is limited by the speed at which chemicals in the cell can move about.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For lead-acid cells, the relationship between time and discharge rate is described by Peukert's law; a lead-acid cell that can no longer sustain a usable terminal voltage at a high current may still have usable capacity, if discharged at a much lower rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Data sheets for rechargeable cells often list the discharge capacity on 8-hour or 20-hour or other stated time; cells for uninterruptible power supply systems may be rated at 15-minute discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The terminal voltage of the battery is not constant during charging and discharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Some types have relatively constant voltage during discharge over much of their capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Non-rechargeable alkaline and zinc–carbon cells output 1.5 V when new, but this voltage drops with use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Most NiMH AA and AAA cells are rated at 1.2 V, but have a flatter discharge curve than alkalines and can usually be used in equipment designed to use alkaline batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Battery manufacturers' technical notes often refer to voltage per cell (VPC) for the individual cells that make up the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For example, to charge a 12 V lead-acid battery (containing 6 cells of 2 V each) at 2.3 VPC requires a voltage of 13.8 V across the battery's terminals.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Subjecting a discharged cell to a current in the direction which tends to discharge it further to the point the positive and negative terminals switch polarity causes a condition called *cell reversal*.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Generally, pushing current through a discharged cell in this way causes undesirable and irreversible chemical reactions to occur, resulting in permanent damage to the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] In the latter case, the problem occurs due to the different cells in a battery having slightly different capacities.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] When one cell reaches discharge level ahead of the rest, the remaining cells will force the current through the discharged cell.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Many battery-operated devices have a low-voltage cutoff that prevents deep discharges from occurring that might cause cell reversal.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] A smart battery has voltage monitoring circuitry built inside.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Cell reversal can occur to a weakly charged cell even before it is fully discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] If the battery drain current is high enough, the cell's internal resistance can create a resistive voltage drop that is greater than the cell's forward emf.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] This results in the reversal of the cell's polarity while the current is flowing.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The higher the required discharge rate of a battery, the better matched the cells should be, both in the type of cell and state of charge, in order to reduce the chances of cell reversal.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] In some situations, such as when correcting NiCd batteries that have been previously overcharged, it may be desirable to fully discharge a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] To avoid damage from the cell reversal effect, it is necessary to access each cell separately: each cell is individually discharged by connecting a load clip across the terminals of each cell, thereby avoiding cell reversal.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] If a multi-cell battery is fully discharged, it will often be damaged due to the cell reversal effect mentioned above.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] It is possible however to fully discharge a battery without causing cell reversal—either by discharging each cell separately, or by allowing each cell's internal leakage to dissipate its charge over time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Even if a cell is brought to a fully discharged state without reversal, however, damage may occur over time simply due to remaining in the discharged state.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] An example of this is the sulfation that occurs in lead-acid batteries that are left sitting on a shelf for long periods.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For this reason it is often recommended to charge a battery that is intended to remain in storage, and to maintain its charge level by periodically recharging it.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Since damage may also occur if the battery is overcharged, the optimal level of charge during storage is typically around 30% to 70%.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Depth of discharge (DOD) is normally stated as a percentage of the nominal ampere-hour capacity; 0% DOD means no discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] As the usable capacity of a battery system depends on the rate of discharge and the allowable voltage at the end of discharge, the depth of discharge must be qualified to show the way it is to be measured.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Due to variations during manufacture and aging, the DOD for complete discharge can change over time or number of charge cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Generally a rechargeable battery system will tolerate more charge/discharge cycles if the DOD is lower on each cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Lithium batteries can discharge to about 80 to 90% of their nominal capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Lead-acid batteries can discharge to about 50–60%.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] While flow batteries can discharge 100%.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] If batteries are used repeatedly even without mistreatment, they lose capacity as the number of charge cycles increases, until they are eventually considered to have reached the end of their useful life.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Different battery systems have differing mechanisms for wearing out.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For example, in lead-acid batteries, not all the active material is restored to the plates on each charge/discharge cycle; eventually enough material is lost that the battery capacity is reduced.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] In lithium-ion types, especially on deep discharge, some reactive lithium metal can be formed on charging, which is no longer available to participate in the next discharge cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Sealed batteries may lose moisture from their liquid electrolyte, especially if overcharged or operated at high temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Recharging time is an important parameter to the user of a product powered by rechargeable batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Even if the charging power supply provides enough power to operate the device as well as recharge the battery, the device is attached to an external power supply during the charging time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For electric vehicles used industrially, charging during off-shifts may be acceptable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For highway electric vehicles, rapid charging is necessary for charging in a reasonable time.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] A rechargeable battery cannot be recharged at an arbitrarily high rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The internal resistance of the battery will produce heat, and excessive temperature rise will damage or destroy a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For some types, the maximum charging rate will be limited by the speed at which active material can diffuse through a liquid electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] High charging rates may produce excess gas in a battery, or may result in damaging side reactions that permanently lower the battery capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Very roughly, and with many exceptions and caveats, restoring a battery's full capacity in one hour or less is considered fast charging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] A battery charger system will include more complex control-circuit- and charging strategies for fast charging, than for a charger designed for slower recharging.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The active components in a secondary cell are the chemicals that make up the positive and negative active materials, and the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The positive and negative electrodes are made up of different materials, with the positive exhibiting a reduction potential and the negative having an oxidation potential.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The sum of the potentials from these half-reactions is the standard cell potential or voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] In primary cells the positive and negative electrodes are known as the cathode and anode, respectively.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Although this convention is sometimes carried through to rechargeable systems—especially with lithium-ion cells, because of their origins in primary lithium cells—this practice can lead to confusion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] In rechargeable cells the positive electrode is the cathode on discharge and the anode on charge, and vice versa for the negative electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The lead–acid battery, invented in 1859 by French physicist Gaston Planté, is the oldest type of rechargeable battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Despite having a very low energy-to-weight ratio and a low energy-to-volume ratio, its ability to supply high surge currents means that the cells have a relatively large power-to-weight ratio.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] These features, along with the low cost, makes it attractive for use in motor vehicles to provide the high current required by automobile starter motors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The nickel–cadmium battery (NiCd) was invented by Waldemar Jungner of Sweden in 1899.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] It uses nickel oxide hydroxide and metallic cadmium as electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Cadmium is a toxic element, and was banned for most uses by the European Union in 2004.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Nickel–cadmium batteries have been almost completely superseded by nickel–metal hydride (NiMH) batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The nickel–iron battery (NiFe) was also developed by Waldemar Jungner in 1899; and commercialized by Thomas Edison in 1901 in the United States for electric vehicles and railway signalling.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] It is composed of only non-toxic elements, unlike many kinds of batteries that contain toxic mercury, cadmium, or lead.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The nickel–metal hydride battery (NiMH) became available in 1989.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] These are now a common consumer and industrial type.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The battery has a hydrogen-absorbing alloy for the negative electrode instead of cadmium.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The lithium-ion battery was introduced in the market in 1991, is the choice in most consumer electronics, having the best energy density and a very slow loss of charge when not in use.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] It does have drawbacks too, particularly the risk of unexpected ignition from the heat generated by the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Such incidents are rare and according to experts, they can be minimized "via appropriate design, installation, procedures and layers of safeguards" so the risk is acceptable.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Lithium-ion polymer batteries (LiPo) are light in weight, offer slightly higher energy density than Li-ion at slightly higher cost, and can be made in any shape.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] They are available but have not displaced Li-ion in the market.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] A primary use is for LiPo batteries is in powering remote-controlled cars, boats and airplanes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] LiPo packs are readily available on the consumer market, in various configurations, up to 44.4 V, for powering certain R/C vehicles and helicopters or drones.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Some test reports warn of the risk of fire when the batteries are not used in accordance with the instructions.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Independent reviews of the technology discuss the risk of fire and explosion from lithium-ion batteries under certain conditions because they use liquid electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Several types of lithium–sulfur battery have been developed, and numerous research groups and organizations have demonstrated that batteries based on lithium sulfur can achieve superior energy density to other lithium technologies.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Whereas lithium-ion batteries offer energy density in the range of 150–260 Wh/kg, batteries based on lithium-sulfur are expected to achieve 450–500 Wh/kg, and can eliminate cobalt, nickel and manganese from the production process.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Furthermore, while initially lithium-sulfur batteries suffered from stability problems, recent research has made advances in developing lithium-sulfur batteries that cycle as long as (or longer than) batteries based on conventional lithium-ion technologies.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The thin-film battery (TFB) is a refinement of lithium ion technology by Excellatron.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The developers claim a large increase in recharge cycles to around 40,000 and higher charge and discharge rates, at least 5 *C* charge rate.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Sustained 60 *C* discharge and 1000 *C* peak discharge rate and a significant increase in specific energy, and energy density.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] lithium iron phosphate batteries are used in some applications.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] UltraBattery has kW and MW-scale installations in place in Australia, Japan, and the U.S.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] It has also been subjected to extensive testing in hybrid electric vehicles and has been shown to last more than 100,000 vehicle miles in on-road commercial testing in a courier vehicle.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The technology is claimed to have a lifetime of 7 to 10 times that of conventional lead-acid batteries in high rate partial state-of-charge use, with safety and environmental benefits claimed over competitors like lithium-ion.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Its manufacturer suggests an almost 100% recycling rate is already in place for the product.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The potassium-ion battery delivers around a million cycles, due to the extraordinary electrochemical stability of potassium insertion/extraction materials such as Prussian blue.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The sodium-ion battery is meant for stationary storage and competes with lead–acid batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] It aims at a low total cost of ownership per kWh of storage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] This is achieved by a long and stable lifetime.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The effective number of cycles is above 5000 and the battery is not damaged by deep discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] The energy density is rather low, somewhat lower than lead–acid.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] A rechargeable battery is only one of several types of rechargeable energy storage systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Several alternatives to rechargeable batteries exist or are under development.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] For uses such as portable radios, rechargeable batteries may be replaced by clockwork mechanisms which are wound up by hand, driving dynamos, although this system may be used to charge a battery rather than to operate the radio directly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Flashlights may be driven by a dynamo directly.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Ultracapacitors – capacitors of extremely high value – are also used; an electric screwdriver which charges in 90 seconds and will drive about half as many screws as a device using a rechargeable battery was introduced in 2007, and similar flashlights have been produced.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Ultracapacitors are being developed for transportation, using a large capacitor to store energy instead of the rechargeable battery banks used in hybrid vehicles.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] One drawback of capacitors compared to batteries is that the terminal voltage drops rapidly; a capacitor that has 25% of its initial energy left in it will have one-half of its initial voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] By contrast, battery systems tend to have a terminal voltage that does not decline rapidly until nearly exhausted.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] This terminal voltage drop complicates the design of power electronics for use with ultracapacitors.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] However, there are potential benefits in cycle efficiency, lifetime, and weight compared with rechargeable systems.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] China started using ultracapacitors on two commercial bus routes in 2006; one of them is route 11 in Shanghai.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] Flow batteries, used for specialized applications, are recharged by replacing the electrolyte liquid.
[src:battery-chemistry-embedded/rechargeable-battery] A flow battery can be considered to be a type of rechargeable fuel cell.
